{"title_page": "Operation Pastorius", "text_new": "{{short description|Attempted WWII German sabotage operation against the Continental U.S.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{operational plan\n| name        = Operation Pastorius\n| partof      = the [[American Theater (1939-1945)|American Theater]] of [[World War II]]\n| image       = [[File:Nazi saboteur trial.jpg|325px]]\n| caption     = The trial of the captured Germans, July 1942.\n| objective   = [[Sabotage]] American economic infrastructure\n| date        = June 1942\n| executed_by = Nazi Germany\n| outcome     = Failed\n}}\n{{North American Theater}}\n\n'''Operation Pastorius''' was a failed [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Espionage|intelligence]] plan for [[sabotage]] inside the [[United States]] during [[World War II]]. The operation was staged in June 1942 and was to be directed against strategic American economic targets. The operation was named by [[Admiral]] [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''[[Abwehr]]'', for [[Francis Daniel Pastorius]], the leader of the first organized settlement of Germans in America.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941, followed by [[German declaration of war against the United States (1941)|Nazi Germany's declaration of war on the United States]] four days later<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/germany-declares-war-on-the-united-states|title=Germany declares war on the United States - Dec 11, 1941 - HISTORY.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> (and the [[United States declaration of war upon Germany (1941)|United States' declaration of war on Germany]] in response), [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] authorized a mission to sabotage the American war effort and attack civilian targets to [[Demoralization (warfare)|demoralize]] the American civilian population inside the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title=Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States |author=Alex Abella, Scott Gordon |date=January 2003 |page=[https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 17] |publisher=The Lyons Press |isbn=1-5857-4722-X |url=https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 }}</ref> The mission was headed by Admiral [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''Abwehr''. Canaris recalled that during [[World War I]], he organized the sabotage of French installations in Morocco, and entered the United States with other German agents to plant bombs in New York arms factories, including the [[Black Tom explosion|destruction of munitions supplies at Black Tom Island]], in 1916. He hoped that Operation Pastorius would have the same kind of success they had in 1916.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peculiar Liaisons in War, Espionage, and Terrorism of the Twentieth Century |author=John Craig |date=2 February 2004 |page=170 |publisher=Algora Publishing |isbn=0-8758-6331-0 }}</ref>\n\n==Agents==\nRecruited for Operation Pastorius were eight German residents who had lived in the United States. Two of them, [[Ernst Burger]] and [[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]], were American citizens. The others, [[George John Dasch]], Edward John Kerling, [[Richard Quirin]], Heinrich Harm Heinck, Hermann Otto Neubauer, and Werner Thiel, had worked at various jobs in the United States. All eight were recruited into the ''Abwehr'' [[military intelligence]] organization and were given three weeks of intensive sabotage training in the [[Oberkommando der Wehrmacht|German High Command]] school on an estate at [[Quenzsee|Quenz Lake]], near [[Berlin]], [[Germany]]. The agents were instructed in the manufacture and use of [[Explosive material|explosives]], [[Incendiary device|incendiaries]], [[Blasting cap|primers]], and various forms of mechanical, chemical, and electrical delayed timing devices. Considerable time was spent developing complete background \"histories\" they were to use in the United States. They were encouraged to converse in English and to read American newspapers and  magazines to hone their English and familiarity with current American events and culture.<ref name=\"Foes\">{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=131 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\n==Mission==\n\nTheir mission was to stage sabotage attacks on American economic targets: [[hydroelectric plant]]s at [[Niagara Falls]]; the [[Alcoa|Aluminum Company of America]]'s plants in [[Illinois]], [[Tennessee]], and [[New York (state)|New York]]; [[McAlpine Locks and Dam|locks]] on the [[Ohio River]] near [[Louisville, Kentucky]]; the [[Horseshoe Curve (Pennsylvania)|Horseshoe Curve]], a crucial railroad pass near [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]], as well as the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]'s [[Altoona Works|repair shops]] at Altoona;<ref>[http://www.trainweb.org/horseshoecurve-nrhs/Guide.htm Horseshoe Curve, NRHS - Railfan's Guide to the Altoona Area](Requires Java 1.6 as of 1 January 2009]</ref> a [[cryolite]] plant in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]]; [[Hell Gate Bridge]] in New York; and [[Pennsylvania Station (Newark)|Pennsylvania Station]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. The agents were also instructed to spread a wave of terror by planting explosives on [[bridge]]s, [[Train station|railroad station]]s, water facilities, and [[Public space|public places]]. They were given [[counterfeit]] [[birth certificate]]s, [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] Cards, [[Conscription|draft]] deferment cards, nearly $175,000 in American money, and [[driver's license]]s, and put aboard two [[U-boat]]s to land on the east coast of the U.S.<ref name=\"Foes\" />\n\nBefore the mission began, it was in danger of being compromised, as George Dasch, head of the team, left sensitive documents behind on a train, and one of the agents when drunk announced to patrons at a bar in [[Paris]] that he was a secret agent.<ref>{{cite book |last= Dobbs |first= Michael |title= Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America |url= https://archive.org/details/saboteursnazirai00dobb |url-access= registration |publisher= [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]] |date=February 2004 |isbn= 978-0-375-41470-1}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of June 12, 1942, the first submarine to arrive in the U.S., {{GS|U-202||2}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u202.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-202 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> landed at [[Amagansett, New York]], which is about 100 miles east of [[New York City]], on [[Long Island]], at what today is Atlantic Avenue beach. It was carrying Dasch and three other saboteurs (Burger, Quirin, and Heinck). The team came ashore wearing [[Uniforms and insignia of the Kriegsmarine|German Navy uniform]]s so that if they were captured, they would be classified as [[prisoners of war]] rather than [[espionage|spies]].<ref>[http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf Judicial Review for Enemy Fighters: The Court\u2019s Fateful Turn in Ex parte Quirin, the Nazi Saboteur Case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001757/http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf |date=3 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Battle\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gq-pOED4TSUC&pg=PT98&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Scorpions: The Battles and Triumphs of FDR's Great Supreme Court Justices |author=Noah Feldman |date=8 November 2010 |page=186 |publisher=[[Hachette Book Group USA]] |isbn=0-4465-8057-0 |accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> They also brought their explosives, primers and incendiaries, and buried them along with their uniforms, and put on civilian clothes to begin an expected two-year campaign in the sabotage of American defense-related production.<ref>[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs], FBI Famous Cases</ref>\n\nWhen Dasch was discovered amidst the dunes by unarmed [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guardsman]] John C. Cullen, Dasch offered Cullen a $260 bribe.<ref>\nElke Frenzel, [http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/0,1518,716753,00.html Hitler's Unfulfilled Dream of a New York in Flames] ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' 16 September 2010</ref> Cullen feigned cooperation but reported the encounter. An armed patrol returned to the site but found only the buried equipment; the Germans had taken the [[Long Island Rail Road]] from the [[Amagansett (LIRR station)|Amagansett station]] into [[Manhattan]], where they checked into a hotel. A massive [[Manhunt (military)|manhunt]] was begun.\n\nThe other four-member German team headed by Kerling landed without incident at [[Ponte Vedra Beach, Florida]], south of [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] on June 16, 1942. They came on {{GS|U-584||2}}, another submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u584.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-584 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> This group came ashore wearing [[bathing suit]]s but wore German Navy hats. After landing ashore, they threw away their hats, put on civilian clothes, and started their mission by boarding trains to [[Chicago, Illinois]] and [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Battle\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1372973/Revealed-The-secret-Nazi-operation-Pastorius-land-German-soldiers-U-S-soil-sabotage-war-effort-world-war-two.html |title=Hitler sent German U-boat carrying secret agents to terrorise New York during World War Two (but it got wedged off Long Island) |author=Kevin Dougherty |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe two teams were to meet on July 4 in a hotel in Cincinnati to coordinate their sabotage operations.<ref>Page 130, The Florida Historical Quarterly, Volume 49</ref>\n\n==Betrayal==\nDasch called Burger into their upper-story hotel room and opened a window, saying they would talk, and if they disagreed, \"only one of us will walk out that door\u2014the other will fly out this window.\" Dasch told him he had no intention of going through with the mission, hated [[Nazism]], and planned to report the plot to the [[FBI]]. Burger agreed to defect to the United States immediately.<ref name=\"McCann2006\">{{cite book|author=Joseph T. McCann|title=Terrorism on American Soil: A Concise History of Plots and Perpetrators from the Famous to the Forgotten|url=https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=Sentient Publications|isbn=978-1-59181-049-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose/page/81 81]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Dobbs2007\">{{cite book|author=Michael Dobbs|title=Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWOKF8-fZtAC&pg=PA119|date=18 December 2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-42755-7|pages=119\u2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, Dasch phoned the New York office of the FBI to explain who he was, but hung up when the agent answering doubted his story. Four days later, he took a train to [[Washington, DC]] and walked into FBI headquarters, where he gained the attention of Assistant Director D.{{nbsp}}M. Ladd by showing him the operation's budget of $84,000 cash.<ref name=\"Dobbs2007\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Helluva Town: The Story of New York City During World War II |author=Richard Goldstein |date=13 April 2010 |page=40 |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |isbn=1-4165-8996-1 }}</ref> Besides Burger, none of the other German agents knew they were betrayed. Over the next two weeks, Burger and the other six were arrested.  FBI Director [[J. Edgar Hoover]] made no mention that Dasch had turned himself in, and claimed credit for the FBI for cracking the spy ring.<ref name=\"wapomonument\" />\n\n==Mugshots==\n<gallery class=\"center\" heights=\"175px\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:George John Dasch.jpg|[[George John Dasch]]\nFile:Ernest Peter Burger.jpg|[[Ernst Peter Burger]]\nFile:Herbert Haupt - mugshot.jpg|[[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]]\nFile:Heinrich Heinck - mugshot.jpg|[[Heinrich Heinck]]\nFile:Edward John Kerling - mugshot.jpg|[[Eddie Kerling]]\nFile:Herman Otto Neubauer.jpg|[[Herman Otto Neubauer]]\nFile:Richard Quirin - mugshot.jpg|[[Richard Quirin]]\nFile:Werner Thiel - mugshot.jpg|[[Werner Thiel]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Trial and execution==\nFearful that a civilian court would be too lenient, President Roosevelt issued Executive Proclamation 2561 on 2 July 1942 creating a [[military tribunal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=16281|title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Proclamation 2561\u2014Denying Certain Enemies Access to the Courts|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> to prosecute the Germans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/metro/2010-07-12/story/agents-picked-ponte-vedra-landing-point-1942 |title=A Look Back: Nazi agents picked Ponte Vedra as landing point in 1942 |author=Jessie-Lynne Kerr |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[The Florida Times-Union]]}}</ref> Placed before a seven-member military commission, the Germans were charged with the following offenses:\n\n:* 1) Violating the [[law of war]];\n:* 2) Violating Article 81 of the [[Articles of War#United States|Articles of War]], defining the offense of corresponding with or giving intelligence to the enemy;\n:* 3) Violating Article 82 of the Articles of War, defining the offense of spying; and\n:* 4) [[Conspiracy]] to commit the offenses alleged in the first three charges.\n\nThe trial was held in Assembly Hall #1 on the fifth floor of the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] building in Washington D.C. on 8 July 1942.<ref>{{cite book|title=Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage |author=Joseph E. Persico |page=204 | publisher=[[Random House]]| date=22 October 2002 | isbn=0-3757-6126-8}}</ref> Lawyers for the accused, who included [[Lauson Stone]] and [[Kenneth Royall]], attempted to have the case tried in a civilian court but were rebuffed by the [[United States Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ex parte Quirin]]'', 317 U.S. 1 (1942), a case that was later cited as a precedent for the trial by military commission of any [[unlawful combatant]] against the United States.\n\nThe trial for the eight defendants ended on 1 August 1942. Two days later, all were found guilty and sentenced to death. Roosevelt commuted Burger's sentence to life in prison and Dasch's to 30 years because they had turned themselves in and provided information about the others. The others were executed on  8 August 1942 in the [[electric chair]] on the third floor of the District of Columbia jail and buried in a [[potter's field]] in the [[Blue Plains (Washington, D.C.)|Blue Plains]] neighborhood in the [[Anacostia]] area of Washington.\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe failure of Operation Pastorius led Hitler to rebuke Admiral Canaris and no sabotage attempt was ever made again in the United States. During the remaining years of the war, the Germans only once more dispatched agents to the United States by submarine. In November 1944, as part of [[Operation Elster]] a German submarine, [[German submarine U-1230|U-1230]], dropped two [[SS-Reichssicherheitshauptamt|RSHA]] spies off the coast of [[Maine]] to gather intelligence on American manufacturing and technical progress. The FBI captured both men shortly after.<ref name=\"Miller2013\">{{cite book|author=Robert A. Miller|title=A True Story of An American Nazi Spy: William Curtis Colepaugh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ndSkplZUUh8C&pg=PA73&dq=%22There+is+not+one+word+of+reference+to+sabotaging+the+atom+bomb%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifjZb-wJrVAhWDgj4KHXZ9CXcQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=%22There%20is%20not%20one%20word%20of%20reference%20to%20sabotaging%20the%20atom%20bomb%22&f=false|date=27 February 2013|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4669-8219-2|pages=73\u2013}}</ref> These agents benefited from the calmer state of public nerves in the later years of the war and received prison sentences rather than execution.<ref>{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=133 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, President [[Harry S. Truman]] granted executive clemency to Dasch and Burger on the condition that they be deported to the [[American Zone of Occupation#American Zone of Occupation|American Zone of occupied Germany]]. They were not welcomed back in Germany, as they were regarded as traitors who had caused the death of their [[Comrade|comrades]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Shoot or hang themselves? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7859070.html|newspaper=Der Spiegel|number=15|language=German|date=6 April 1998}}</ref> Although they had been promised pardons by Hoover in exchange for their cooperation, both men died without ever receiving them{{Explain-wrap|date=March 2020|reason=Who are \"them\"?}}. Dasch died in 1992 at the age of 89 in [[Ludwigshafen]], [[Germany]]. Burger died in 1975.\n\nSometime in the 1960s or 1970s, the [[National Socialist White People's Party]] placed an unauthorized monument to the executed spies in a thicket in southwest Washington, D.C. on National Park Service land. It went largely unknown and ignored for several decades; the Park Service removed it in 2010.<ref name=\"wapomonument\">{{cite news |last=Cox |first=John Woodrow |date=June 23, 2017 |title=Six Nazi spies were executed in D.C. White supremacists gave them a memorial \u2014 on federal land. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/23/six-nazi-spies-were-executed-in-d-c-white-supremacists-gave-them-a-memorial-on-federal-land/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=June 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Duquesne Spy Ring]]\n*''[[They Came to Blow Up America]]'', a 1943 film based on Operation Pastorius, starring [[George Sanders]]\n*''[[Saboteur (film)|Saboteur]]'', a 1942 film revolving around acts of sabotage on the US mainland during World War II.\n*[[New York at War]], military parade held at same time\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?181143-1/saboteurs-nazi-raid-america ''Booknotes'' interview with Michael Dobbs on ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America'', 28 March 2004], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n*Dobbs, Michael, ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America,'' New York: Knopf, 2004. {{ISBN|0-375-41470-3}}\n*Rachlis, Eugene, ''They Came to Kill: The Story of Eight Nazi Saboteurs in America'', New York: Random House, 1961.\n*[[Joseph E. Persico|Persico, Joseph E.]], ''Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage'', New York:Random House, 2001, pp.&nbsp;199\u2013205. {{ISBN|0-375-50246-7}}\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs]\n*[http://www.usswashington.com/dl10ju42.htm Lippmann, David H., ''World War II Plus 55, June 10-13th, 1942'']\n*[http://www.montauklife.com/history/history_night_of_the_nazis.html Montauk Life: The Night of the Nazis]\n*[https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/historics/USSC_CR_0317_0001_ZS.html Cornell University School of Law: ''Ex Parte Quirin'' (summary)]\n*Samaha, Joel, ''et al.'' (eds.), ''Transcript of Proceedings before the Military Commission to Try Persons Charged with Offenses against the Law of War and the Articles of War, Washington D.C., 8 to 31 July 1942'', Minneapolis: University of Minnesota, 2004. [http://www.soc.umn.edu/~samaha/nazi_saboteurs/indexnazi.htm]\n*Abella, Alex & Gordon, Scott, ''Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States'', Guilford, CT: Lyons Press, 2002. {{ISBN|1-58574-722-X}}\n\n'''Further information'''\n*[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/Radio_Episode.aspx?sched=1019 The Facts Don't Matter] An hour-long ''This American Life'' radio episode (original air date 3/12/2004) about the events leading up to ''Ex parte Quirin''\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Operation Pastorius}}\n*[http://ghostsofdc.org/2012/02/09/six-nazi-saboteurs-executed-in-washington/ Six Nazi  Saboteurs Executed in Washington] - Ghosts of DC history blog\n*{{IMDb title|id=0036426 |title= They Came to Blow Up America}} - a 1943 film about saboteurs, led by a German-American, landing on Long Island\n*{{cite newspaper |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/03/nyregion/john-cullen-coast-guardsman-who-detected-spies-dies-at-90.html |title= John Cullen, Coast Guardsman Who Detected Spies, Dies at 90 |author= Richard Goldstein |date= September 2, 2011 |work= The New York Times}}\n\n[[Category:1942 in the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II espionage]]\n[[Category:Economic warfare]]\n[[Category:United States military law]]\n[[Category:Abwehr operations]]\n[[Category:Military operations of World War II involving Germany|Pastorius]]\n[[Category:American Theater of World War II]]\n[[Category:1942 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1942 in Florida]]\n[[Category:1942 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:June 1942 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Attempted WWII German sabotage operation against the Continental U.S.}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{operational plan\n| name        = Operation Pastorius\n| partof      = the [[American Theater (1939-1945)|American Theater]] of [[World War II]]\n| image       = [[File:Nazi saboteur trial.jpg|325px]]\n| caption     = The trial of the captured Germans, July 1942.\n| objective   = [[Sabotage]] American economic infrastructure\n| date        = June 1942\n| executed_by = Nazi Germany\n| outcome     = Failed\n}}\n{{North American Theater}}\n\n'''Operation Pastorius''' was a failed [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Espionage|intelligence]] plan for [[sabotage]] inside the [[United States]] during [[World War II]]. The operation was staged in June 1942 and was to be directed against strategic American economic targets. The operation was named by [[Admiral]] [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''[[Abwehr]]'', for [[Francis Daniel Pastorius]], the leader of the first organized settlement of Germans in America.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941, followed by [[German declaration of war against the United States (1941)|Nazi Germany's declaration of war on the United States]] four days later<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/germany-declares-war-on-the-united-states|title=Germany declares war on the United States - Dec 11, 1941 - HISTORY.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> (and the [[United States declaration of war upon Germany (1941)|United States' declaration of war on Germany]] in response), [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] authorized a mission to sabotage the American war effort and attack civilian targets to [[Demoralization (warfare)|demoralize]] the American civilian population inside the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title=Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States |author=Alex Abella, Scott Gordon |date=January 2003 |page=[https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 17] |publisher=The Lyons Press |isbn=1-5857-4722-X |url=https://archive.org/details/shadowenemieshit00abel_0/page/17 }}</ref> The mission was headed by Admiral [[Wilhelm Canaris]], chief of the German ''Abwehr''. Canaris recalled that during [[World War I]], he organized the sabotage of French installations in Morocco, and entered the United States with other German agents to plant bombs in New York arms factories, including the [[Black Tom explosion|destruction of munitions supplies at Black Tom Island]], in 1916. He hoped that Operation Pastorius would have the same kind of success they had in 1916.<ref>{{cite book |title=Peculiar Liaisons in War, Espionage, and Terrorism of the Twentieth Century |author=John Craig |date=2 February 2004 |page=170 |publisher=Algora Publishing |isbn=0-8758-6331-0 }}</ref>\n\n==Agents==\nRecruited for Operation Pastorius were eight German residents who had lived in the United States. Two of them, [[Ernst Burger]] and [[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]], were American citizens. The others, [[George John Dasch]], Edward John Kerling, [[Richard Quirin]], Heinrich Harm Heinck, Hermann Otto Neubauer, and Werner Thiel, had worked at various jobs in the United States. All eight were recruited into the ''Abwehr'' [[military intelligence]] organization and were given three weeks of intensive sabotage training in the [[Oberkommando der Wehrmacht|German High Command]] school on an estate at [[Quenzsee|Quenz Lake]], near [[Berlin]], [[Germany]]. The agents were instructed in the manufacture and use of [[Explosive material|explosives]], [[Incendiary device|incendiaries]], [[Blasting cap|primers]], and various forms of mechanical, chemical, and electrical delayed timing devices. Considerable time was spent developing complete background \"histories\" they were to use in the United States. They were encouraged to converse in English and to read American newspapers and  magazines to hone their English and familiarity with current American events and culture.<ref name=\"Foes\">{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=131 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\n==Mission==\n\nTheir mission was to stage sabotage attacks on American economic targets: [[hydroelectric plant]]s at [[Niagara Falls]]; the [[Alcoa|Aluminum Company of America]]'s plants in [[Illinois]], [[Tennessee]], and [[New York (state)|New York]]; [[McAlpine Locks and Dam|locks]] on the [[Ohio River]] near [[Louisville, Kentucky]]; the [[Horseshoe Curve (Pennsylvania)|Horseshoe Curve]], a crucial railroad pass near [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]], as well as the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]'s [[Altoona Works|repair shops]] at Altoona;<ref>[http://www.trainweb.org/horseshoecurve-nrhs/Guide.htm Horseshoe Curve, NRHS - Railfan's Guide to the Altoona Area](Requires Java 1.6 as of 1 January 2009]</ref> a [[cryolite]] plant in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]]; [[Hell Gate Bridge]] in New York; and [[Pennsylvania Station (Newark)|Pennsylvania Station]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. The agents were also instructed to spread a wave of terror by planting explosives on [[bridge]]s, [[Train station|railroad station]]s, water facilities, and [[Public space|public places]]. They were given [[counterfeit]] [[birth certificate]]s, [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] Cards, [[Conscription|draft]] deferment cards, nearly $175,000 in American money, and [[driver's license]]s, and put aboard two [[U-boat]]s to land on the east coast of the U.S.<ref name=\"Foes\" />\n\nBefore the mission began, it was in danger of being compromised, as George Dasch, head of the team, left sensitive documents behind on a train, and one of the agents when drunk announced to patrons at a bar in [[Paris]] that he was a secret agent.<ref>{{cite book |last= Dobbs |first= Michael |title= Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America |url= https://archive.org/details/saboteursnazirai00dobb |url-access= registration |publisher= [[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]] |date=February 2004 |isbn= 978-0-375-41470-1}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of June 12, 1942, the first submarine to arrive in the U.S., {{GS|U-202||2}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u202.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-202 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> landed at [[Amagansett, New York]], which is about 100 miles east of [[New York City]], on [[Long Island]], at what today is Atlantic Avenue beach. It was carrying Dasch and three other saboteurs (Burger, Quirin, and Heinck). The team came ashore wearing [[Uniforms and insignia of the Kriegsmarine|German Navy uniform]]s so that if they were captured, they would be classified as [[prisoners of war]] rather than [[espionage|spies]].<ref>[http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf Judicial Review for Enemy Fighters: The Court\u2019s Fateful Turn in Ex parte Quirin, the Nazi Saboteur Case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203001757/http://www.vanderbiltlawreview.org/content/articles/2013/01/Kent_66_Vand_L_Rev_153.pdf |date=3 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Battle\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gq-pOED4TSUC&pg=PT98&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Scorpions: The Battles and Triumphs of FDR's Great Supreme Court Justices |author=Noah Feldman |date=8 November 2010 |page=186 |publisher=[[Hachette Book Group USA]] |isbn=0-4465-8057-0 |accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> They also brought their explosives, primers and incendiaries, and buried them along with their uniforms, and put on civilian clothes to begin an expected two-year campaign in the sabotage of American defense-related production.<ref>[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs], FBI Famous Cases</ref>\n\nWhen Dasch was discovered amidst the dunes by unarmed [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guardsman]] John C. Cullen, Dasch offered Cullen a $260 bribe.<ref>\nElke Frenzel, [http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/0,1518,716753,00.html Hitler's Unfulfilled Dream of a New York in Flames] ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' 16 September 2010</ref> Cullen feigned cooperation but reported the encounter. An armed patrol returned to the site but found only the buried equipment; the Germans had taken the [[Long Island Rail Road]] from the [[Amagansett (LIRR station)|Amagansett station]] into [[Manhattan]], where they checked into a hotel. A massive [[Manhunt (military)|manhunt]] was begun.\n\nThe other four-member German team headed by Kerling landed without incident at [[Ponte Vedra Beach, Florida]], south of [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] on June 16, 1942. They came on {{GS|U-584||2}}, another submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/boats/u584.htm|title=The Type VIIC boat U-584 - German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> This group came ashore wearing [[bathing suit]]s but wore German Navy hats. After landing ashore, they threw away their hats, put on civilian clothes, and started their mission by boarding trains to [[Chicago, Illinois]] and [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Battle\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1372973/Revealed-The-secret-Nazi-operation-Pastorius-land-German-soldiers-U-S-soil-sabotage-war-effort-world-war-two.html |title=Hitler sent German U-boat carrying secret agents to terrorise New York during World War Two (but it got wedged off Long Island) |author=Kevin Dougherty |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe two teams were to meet on July 4 in a hotel in Cincinnati to coordinate their sabotage operations.<ref>Page 130, The Florida Historical Quarterly, Volume 49</ref>\n\n==Betrayal==\nDasch called Burger into their upper-story hotel room and opened a window, saying they would talk, and if they disagreed, \"only one of us will walk out that door\u2014the other will fly out this window.\" Dasch told him he had no intention of going through with the mission, hated [[Nazism]], and planned to report the plot to the FBI. Burger agreed to defect to the United States immediately.<ref name=\"McCann2006\">{{cite book|author=Joseph T. McCann|title=Terrorism on American Soil: A Concise History of Plots and Perpetrators from the Famous to the Forgotten|url=https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=Sentient Publications|isbn=978-1-59181-049-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/terrorismonameri00jose/page/81 81]\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Dobbs2007\">{{cite book|author=Michael Dobbs|title=Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWOKF8-fZtAC&pg=PA119|date=18 December 2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-42755-7|pages=119\u2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, Dasch phoned the New York office of the FBI to explain who he was, but hung up when the agent answering doubted his story. Four days later, he took a train to [[Washington, DC]] and walked into FBI headquarters, where he gained the attention of Assistant Director D.{{nbsp}}M. Ladd by showing him the operation's budget of $84,000 cash.<ref name=\"Dobbs2007\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Helluva Town: The Story of New York City During World War II |author=Richard Goldstein |date=13 April 2010 |page=40 |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |isbn=1-4165-8996-1 }}</ref> Besides Burger, none of the other German agents knew they were betrayed. Over the next two weeks, Burger and the other six were arrested.  FBI Chief, Hoover, made no mention that Dasch had turned himself in, and claimed credit for the FBI for cracking the spy ring.<ref name=\"wapomonument\" />\n\n==Mugshots==\n<gallery class=\"center\" heights=\"175px\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:George John Dasch.jpg|[[George John Dasch]]\nFile:Ernest Peter Burger.jpg|[[Ernst Peter Burger]]\nFile:Herbert Haupt - mugshot.jpg|[[Herbert Hans Haupt|Herbert Haupt]]\nFile:Heinrich Heinck - mugshot.jpg|[[Heinrich Heinck]]\nFile:Edward John Kerling - mugshot.jpg|[[Eddie Kerling]]\nFile:Herman Otto Neubauer.jpg|[[Herman Otto Neubauer]]\nFile:Richard Quirin - mugshot.jpg|[[Richard Quirin]]\nFile:Werner Thiel - mugshot.jpg|[[Werner Thiel]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Trial and execution==\nFearful that a civilian court would be too lenient, President Roosevelt issued Executive Proclamation 2561 on 2 July 1942 creating a [[military tribunal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=16281|title=Franklin D. Roosevelt: Proclamation 2561\u2014Denying Certain Enemies Access to the Courts|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> to prosecute the Germans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/metro/2010-07-12/story/agents-picked-ponte-vedra-landing-point-1942 |title=A Look Back: Nazi agents picked Ponte Vedra as landing point in 1942 |author=Jessie-Lynne Kerr |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[The Florida Times-Union]]}}</ref> Placed before a seven-member military commission, the Germans were charged with the following offenses:\n\n:* 1) Violating the [[law of war]];\n:* 2) Violating Article 81 of the [[Articles of War#United States|Articles of War]], defining the offense of corresponding with or giving intelligence to the enemy;\n:* 3) Violating Article 82 of the Articles of War, defining the offense of spying; and\n:* 4) [[Conspiracy]] to commit the offenses alleged in the first three charges.\n\nThe trial was held in Assembly Hall #1 on the fifth floor of the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] building in Washington D.C. on 8 July 1942.<ref>{{cite book|title=Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage |author=Joseph E. Persico |page=204 | publisher=[[Random House]]| date=22 October 2002 | isbn=0-3757-6126-8}}</ref> Lawyers for the accused, who included [[Lauson Stone]] and [[Kenneth Royall]], attempted to have the case tried in a civilian court but were rebuffed by the [[United States Supreme Court]] in ''[[Ex parte Quirin]]'', 317 U.S. 1 (1942), a case that was later cited as a precedent for the trial by military commission of any [[unlawful combatant]] against the United States.\n\nThe trial for the eight defendants ended on 1 August 1942. Two days later, all were found guilty and sentenced to death. Roosevelt commuted Burger's sentence to life in prison and Dasch's to 30 years because they had turned themselves in and provided information about the others. The others were executed on  8 August 1942 in the [[electric chair]] on the third floor of the District of Columbia jail and buried in a [[potter's field]] in the [[Blue Plains (Washington, D.C.)|Blue Plains]] neighborhood in the [[Anacostia]] area of Washington.\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe failure of Operation Pastorius led Hitler to rebuke Admiral Canaris and no sabotage attempt was ever made again in the United States. During the remaining years of the war, the Germans only once more dispatched agents to the United States by submarine. In November 1944, as part of [[Operation Elster]] a German submarine, [[German submarine U-1230|U-1230]], dropped two [[SS-Reichssicherheitshauptamt|RSHA]] spies off the coast of [[Maine]] to gather intelligence on American manufacturing and technical progress. The FBI captured both men shortly after.<ref name=\"Miller2013\">{{cite book|author=Robert A. Miller|title=A True Story of An American Nazi Spy: William Curtis Colepaugh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ndSkplZUUh8C&pg=PA73&dq=%22There+is+not+one+word+of+reference+to+sabotaging+the+atom+bomb%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifjZb-wJrVAhWDgj4KHXZ9CXcQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=%22There%20is%20not%20one%20word%20of%20reference%20to%20sabotaging%20the%20atom%20bomb%22&f=false|date=27 February 2013|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-4669-8219-2|pages=73\u2013}}</ref> These agents benefited from the calmer state of public nerves in the later years of the war and received prison sentences rather than execution.<ref>{{cite book |title=Insidious Foes: The Axis Fifth Column and the American Home Front |author=Francis MacDonnell |date=2 November 1995 |page=133 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=0-1950-9268-6 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, President [[Harry S. Truman]] granted executive clemency to Dasch and Burger on the condition that they be deported to the [[American Zone of Occupation#American Zone of Occupation|American Zone of occupied Germany]]. They were not welcomed back in Germany, as they were regarded as traitors who had caused the death of their [[Comrade|comrades]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Shoot or hang themselves? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7859070.html|newspaper=Der Spiegel|number=15|language=German|date=6 April 1998}}</ref> Although they had been promised pardons by Hoover in exchange for their cooperation, both men died without ever receiving them{{Explain-wrap|date=March 2020|reason=Who are \"them\"?}}. Dasch died in 1992 at the age of 89 in [[Ludwigshafen]], [[Germany]]. Burger died in 1975.\n\nSometime in the 1960s or 1970s, the [[National Socialist White People's Party]] placed an unauthorized monument to the executed spies in a thicket in southwest Washington, D.C. on National Park Service land. It went largely unknown and ignored for several decades; the Park Service removed it in 2010.<ref name=\"wapomonument\">{{cite news |last=Cox |first=John Woodrow |date=June 23, 2017 |title=Six Nazi spies were executed in D.C. White supremacists gave them a memorial \u2014 on federal land. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/23/six-nazi-spies-were-executed-in-d-c-white-supremacists-gave-them-a-memorial-on-federal-land/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=June 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Duquesne Spy Ring]]\n*''[[They Came to Blow Up America]]'', a 1943 film based on Operation Pastorius, starring [[George Sanders]]\n*''[[Saboteur (film)|Saboteur]]'', a 1942 film revolving around acts of sabotage on the US mainland during World War II.\n*[[New York at War]], military parade held at same time\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?181143-1/saboteurs-nazi-raid-america ''Booknotes'' interview with Michael Dobbs on ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America'', 28 March 2004], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n*Dobbs, Michael, ''Saboteurs: The Nazi Raid on America,'' New York: Knopf, 2004. {{ISBN|0-375-41470-3}}\n*Rachlis, Eugene, ''They Came to Kill: The Story of Eight Nazi Saboteurs in America'', New York: Random House, 1961.\n*[[Joseph E. Persico|Persico, Joseph E.]], ''Roosevelt's Secret War: FDR and World War II Espionage'', New York:Random House, 2001, pp.&nbsp;199\u2013205. {{ISBN|0-375-50246-7}}\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/libref/historic/famcases/nazi/nazi.htm Federal Bureau of Investigation: George John Dasch and the Nazi Saboteurs]\n*[http://www.usswashington.com/dl10ju42.htm Lippmann, David H., ''World War II Plus 55, June 10-13th, 1942'']\n*[http://www.montauklife.com/history/history_night_of_the_nazis.html Montauk Life: The Night of the Nazis]\n*[https://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/historics/USSC_CR_0317_0001_ZS.html Cornell University School of Law: ''Ex Parte Quirin'' (summary)]\n*Samaha, Joel, ''et al.'' (eds.), ''Transcript of Proceedings before the Military Commission to Try Persons Charged with Offenses against the Law of War and the Articles of War, Washington D.C., 8 to 31 July 1942'', Minneapolis: University of Minnesota, 2004. [http://www.soc.umn.edu/~samaha/nazi_saboteurs/indexnazi.htm]\n*Abella, Alex & Gordon, Scott, ''Shadow Enemies: Hitler's Secret Terrorist Plot Against the United States'', Guilford, CT: Lyons Press, 2002. {{ISBN|1-58574-722-X}}\n\n'''Further information'''\n*[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/Radio_Episode.aspx?sched=1019 The Facts Don't Matter] An hour-long ''This American Life'' radio episode (original air date 3/12/2004) about the events leading up to ''Ex parte Quirin''\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Operation Pastorius}}\n*[http://ghostsofdc.org/2012/02/09/six-nazi-saboteurs-executed-in-washington/ Six Nazi  Saboteurs Executed in Washington] - Ghosts of DC history blog\n*{{IMDb title|id=0036426 |title= They Came to Blow Up America}} - a 1943 film about saboteurs, led by a German-American, landing on Long Island\n*{{cite newspaper |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/03/nyregion/john-cullen-coast-guardsman-who-detected-spies-dies-at-90.html |title= John Cullen, Coast Guardsman Who Detected Spies, Dies at 90 |author= Richard Goldstein |date= September 2, 2011 |work= The New York Times}}\n\n[[Category:1942 in the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II espionage]]\n[[Category:Economic warfare]]\n[[Category:United States military law]]\n[[Category:Abwehr operations]]\n[[Category:Military operations of World War II involving Germany|Pastorius]]\n[[Category:American Theater of World War II]]\n[[Category:1942 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1942 in Florida]]\n[[Category:1942 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:June 1942 events]]\n", "name_user": "Rontrigger", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBetrayal", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Pastorius"}
{"title_page": "Sitamarhi", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Sita Samahit Sthal}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Sitamarhi\n| native_name_lang       = \n| other_name             = \n| settlement_type        = City\n| image_skyline          = \n| image_caption          = \n| pushpin_map            = India Bihar\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Bihar, India\n| coordinates            = {{coord|26.6|N|85.48|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Bihar]]\n| subdivision_type3      = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Sitamarhi district|Sitamarhi]]\n| subdivision_type2         = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Mithila (region)|Mithila]]\n| established_title      = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date       = \n| unit_pref              = Metric\n| area_total_km2         = \n| elevation_footnotes    = \n| elevation_m            = 56\n| population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"biharonline.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.biharonline.gov.in/Site/Content/General/Dist.aspx?typ=C&id=36&ln=en&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Census of SITAMARHI<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Biharonline.gov.in|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n| population_total       = 106093\n| population_as_of       = 2011\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| demographics_type1     = Languages\n| demographics1_title1   = Official\n| demographics1_info1    = [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Bajjika]]\n| timezone1              = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1            = +5:30\n| postal_code_type       = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code            = 843302, 843301, 843331,843323\n| iso_code               = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-BR]]\n| registration_plate     = BR-30 \n| blank1_name_sec1       = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1       = [[Sitamarhi (Lok Sabha constituency)|Sitamarhi]]\n| blank2_name_sec1       = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1       = [[Sitamarhi (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sitamarhi]]\n| website                = {{URL|sitamarhi.org/}}\n}}\n'''Sitamarhi''' is a city and the district headquarters of the [[Sitamarhi district]] in the [[Mithila (region)|Mithila region]] of [[Bihar]], [[India]] and is a part of the [[Tirhut Division]]. Bihar government has declared Sitamarhi as Municipal Corporation on 8th April of 2020 .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tirhut-muzaffarpur.bih.nic.in|title=Tirhut Division|website=Tirhut-muzaffarpur.bih.nic.in|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nSitamarhi is considered by many to be the birthplace of [[Sita]], the main character of the epic ''[[Ramayana]]''; a temple dedicated to Sita is located at punaura dham Sitamarhi.<ref name=\"temple\">{{cite book |last1=Chakrabarti |first1=Dilip K |title=Archaeological Geography of the Ganga Plain: The Lower and the Middle Ganga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OEZe-wAIiKIC&pg=PA207&dq=sitamarhi+history&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Y6xJUYCDDYWsrAfYt4DQCg&ved=0CF4Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=sitamarhi%20history&f=false |accessdate=20 March 2013 |edition= |volume= |year= 2001|publisher=Orient Blacksawn |location=New Delhi |language= |isbn=9788178240169 |page= 207 }}</ref> A rock-cut sanctuary from the great [[Mauryan Empire|Mauryan]] period is found near Sitamarhi.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sen |first1=S N |title=Ancient Indian History And Civilization |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA166&dq=sitamarhi+history&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lLJJUcSACsbKrAfGx4CgDQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=sitamarhi%20history&f=false|accessdate=20 March 2013 |edition= |volume= |year=1999 |publisher=New Age International |location= |language= |isbn=9788122411980 |page=166 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1875, the Sitamarhi sub-district was created within the [[Muzaffarpur district]].<ref>[http://dc-sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/ Official Website of the District and Civil Court of Sitmahri] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525105109/http://dc-sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/ |date=25 May 2010 }}, Retrieved May 26, 2010</ref> Sitamarhi was detached from the Muzaffarpur district and became a separate district on 11&nbsp;December 1972.<ref name=\"actionplan\">[http://mohfw.nic.in/nrhm/DHAP/DHAP_Bihar/sitamarhi.pdf District Health Action Plan], National Rural Health Mission, Government of Bihar, Retrieved May 25, 2010</ref>  It is situated in the northern part of Bihar. The district headquarters is located in [[Dumra, Sitamarhi|Dumra]], {{convert|5|km|mi|0|spell=in}} south of Sita temple.{{Clarify|reason=the lead says Sitamarhi is the HQ|date=May 2012}}\n\n[[Rama Navami]] is a spring festival in Dumra, widely celebrated with a large fair held to mark the occasion. Also in janki mandir a marriage ceremony of lord ram and sita mata happens every year.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/place/Sitamarhi Sitamarhi], Encyclopedia Britannica (2014), Quote: \"A large Ramanavami fair, celebrating the birth of Lord Rama, is held in spring with considerable trade in pottery, spices, brass ware, and cotton cloth. A cattle fair held in Sitamarhi is the largest in Bihar state. The town is sacred as the birthplace of the goddess Sita (also called Janaki), the wife of Lord Ram.\"</ref> [[Sama Chakeva]] is a prominent winter festival dedicated to celebrate brother-sister relationships.<ref>{{cite web|title=Festivals of Bihar|url=http://gov.bih.nic.in/Profile/festivals.htm|publisher=[[Government of Bihar]]|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> This is a major cultural event with marriage ceremonies and many cultural rituals that take much preparation.<ref>[Mithila kaa Itihas (Hindi Book), Author: Dr. Ram Prakash Sharma, Publisher: Kameshwer Singh Darbhanga Sanskrit University, Darbhanga, Page No.: 460]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSitamarhi, located at {{Coord|26.6|N|85.48|E}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/34/Sitamarhi.html|title=Maps, Weather, and Airports for Sitamarhi, India|website=Fallingrain.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> has an average elevation of {{convert|56|m|ft}}.\n\nThere are multiple small towns that are famous in Sitamarhi, like [[Bairgania]] and Sursand which is located at Indo-Nepal border and is very famous. Few other famous places in Sitamarhi region are Bath Asli , Sonbarsa,Sheohar,Bajpatti,Pupri and Parihar are very good town. Dumra is near Sitamarhi which is known for all the government offices.\n\nRiga village is close to this town and is known for suger mills.\n\n==Demographics==\nSitamarhi city has a total population of around 106,093. There are around 56,693 males, and \n49,400 females. The amount of literate males are 39,537, and the amount of literate females are 29,970. In total 69,507 people are literate. The average literacy rate is 77.03% in total, 81.98% for males, and 71.33% for females. The sexratio is 871. The child sexratio is 872.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census2011.co.in/census/metropolitan/168-sitamarhi.html|title=Sitamarhi District Population Data - Census 2011|website=www.census2011.co.in}}</ref>\n\n=={{anchor|Connectivity}} Transportation==\n[[National Highway 77 (India)|National Highway 77]] connects the area to the [[Muzaffarpur district]] and [[Patna]]. National Highways 77, 104, and other roads connect to the adjoining districts. State highways link it to [[Madhubani district]] in the east and [[Sheohar]] in the west.\n\n[[Sitamarhi Junction railway station]] is a five-platform station on the [[Darbhanga]]\u2013[[Raxaul]]\u2013[[Narkatiaganj]] line, which was converted to broad gauge in February 2014. Another broad-gauge track connects Sitamarhi to [[Muzaffarpur]]. Direct train services are available from Sitamarhi railway junction to places such as New Delhi, Kolkata, Varanasi, Lucknow, Guwahati (Kamakhya), Hyderabad, Kanpur and Mumbai.\n\nThe nearest international airport to Sitamarhi is the [[Jay Prakash Narayan International Airport]] which is about {{convert|120|km|mi}} away.\n\nSitamarhi is connected to cities in and around Bihar by state-owned transport services. Many private buses (both AC and non-AC) operate between Sitamarhi and [[Patna]].\n\n==Media==\nSitamarhi has an [[All India Radio]] (AIR) relay station known as Akashvani Sitamarhi, broadcasting on FM frequencies. People from Sitamarhi have developed a news portal [http://Sitamarhi.org Sitamarhi.org]\n\n==Education==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=March 2018}}\nThe following is a partial list of [[schools in Sitamarhi]]\n*[[Front Age, Kiran Chowk]]\n*[[Bharati uchchangle Vidhayalaya Dumra in front of Hawaii field]]\n*[[Gyan Bharati Prepatory School,Purandaha Rajawara ,Sonbarsa Sitamarhi]]*\n*N.S.D.A.V Public school\n* [[Janki Vidya Niketan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janki_Vidya_Niketan |title=Janki Vidya Niketan - Janki Vidya Niketan|publisher=}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=October 2019}}\n* Kendriya Vidyalaya Jawahar Nagar, Sutihara\n* Saraswati Vidya Mandir, Ring bandh\n*[[S.V.Rising Point school ,old Exchange Road mirchaipatti Sitamarhi]]\n*[[Vidya Bharati school,Shantinagar, Sitamarhi. ]]\n* Hellen's School Sitamarhi\n* Delhi Public School, Lagma\n* Brilliant Public School, Sitamarhi\n*[[Mother's Shadow play and Prepatory Public schooy Pilli Kutti Ring bandh Sitamarhi]]\n* R.O.S. Public School, Khairwa, Riga Road, Sitamarhi\n* [[Sacred Heart School, Sitamarhi|Sacred Heart School]]\n* MP High School (Sitamarhi High School, Dumra) Anand Nagar, Talkhapur, Dumra\n* Mathura High School\n* Sri Gandhi High School, Parihar\n* Lakshmi High School\n* Kamala Girls High School\n*[[Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalaya, Sitamarhi|Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalaya Sitamarhi (JNV Sitmarhi)]]\n*Sun Shine Public School- Shantinagar\n*State middle school-sundargama\n*Vidyamandir Classes in Sitamarhi\n*Sushila singha pmky coching center in Virta Tola Punaura\n* Holy faith public high school, old exchange road\n* Genius Global Academy (Baath Asli)\n\n'Hospitals'\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/District Portal of Sitamarhi]\n* [http://tirhut-muzaffarpur.bih.nic.in Official Website of Tirhut Division]\n\n{{Tirhut Division}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Sitamarhi district]]\n[[Category:Sitamarhi district]]\n[[Category:Places in the Ramayana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Sita Samahit Sthal}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Sitamarhi\n| native_name_lang       = \n| other_name             = \n| settlement_type        = City\n| image_skyline          = \n| image_caption          = \n| pushpin_map            = India Bihar\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Bihar, India\n| coordinates            = {{coord|26.6|N|85.48|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Bihar]]\n| subdivision_type3      = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Sitamarhi district|Sitamarhi]]\n| subdivision_type2         = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Mithila (region)|Mithila]]\n| established_title      = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date       = \n| unit_pref              = Metric\n| area_total_km2         = \n| elevation_footnotes    = \n| elevation_m            = 56\n| population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"biharonline.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.biharonline.gov.in/Site/Content/General/Dist.aspx?typ=C&id=36&ln=en&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Census of SITAMARHI<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Biharonline.gov.in|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n| population_total       = 106093\n| population_as_of       = 2011\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| demographics_type1     = Languages\n| demographics1_title1   = Official\n| demographics1_info1    = [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Bajjika]]\n| timezone1              = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1            = +5:30\n| postal_code_type       = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code            = 843302, 843301, 843331,843323\n| iso_code               = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-BR]]\n| registration_plate     = BR-30 \n| blank1_name_sec1       = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1       = [[Sitamarhi (Lok Sabha constituency)|Sitamarhi]]\n| blank2_name_sec1       = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1       = [[Sitamarhi (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sitamarhi]]\n| website                = {{URL|sitamarhi.org/}}\n}}\n'''Sitamarhi''' is a city and the district headquarters of the [[Sitamarhi district]] in the [[Mithila (region)|Mithila region]] of [[Bihar]], [[India]] and is a part of the [[Tirhut Division]]. Bihar government has declared Sitamarhi as Municipal Corporation on 8th April of 2020 .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tirhut-muzaffarpur.bih.nic.in|title=Tirhut Division|website=Tirhut-muzaffarpur.bih.nic.in|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nSitamarhi is considered by many to be the birthplace of [[Sita]], the main character of the epic ''[[Ramayana]]''; a temple dedicated to Sita is located at punaura dham Sitamarhi.<ref name=\"temple\">{{cite book |last1=Chakrabarti |first1=Dilip K |title=Archaeological Geography of the Ganga Plain: The Lower and the Middle Ganga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OEZe-wAIiKIC&pg=PA207&dq=sitamarhi+history&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Y6xJUYCDDYWsrAfYt4DQCg&ved=0CF4Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=sitamarhi%20history&f=false |accessdate=20 March 2013 |edition= |volume= |year= 2001|publisher=Orient Blacksawn |location=New Delhi |language= |isbn=9788178240169 |page= 207 }}</ref> A rock-cut sanctuary from the great [[Mauryan Empire|Mauryan]] period is found near Sitamarhi.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sen |first1=S N |title=Ancient Indian History And Civilization |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA166&dq=sitamarhi+history&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lLJJUcSACsbKrAfGx4CgDQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=sitamarhi%20history&f=false|accessdate=20 March 2013 |edition= |volume= |year=1999 |publisher=New Age International |location= |language= |isbn=9788122411980 |page=166 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1875, the Sitamarhi sub-district was created within the [[Muzaffarpur district]].<ref>[http://dc-sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/ Official Website of the District and Civil Court of Sitmahri] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525105109/http://dc-sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/ |date=25 May 2010 }}, Retrieved May 26, 2010</ref> Sitamarhi was detached from the Muzaffarpur district and became a separate district on 11&nbsp;December 1972.<ref name=\"actionplan\">[http://mohfw.nic.in/nrhm/DHAP/DHAP_Bihar/sitamarhi.pdf District Health Action Plan], National Rural Health Mission, Government of Bihar, Retrieved May 25, 2010</ref>  It is situated in the northern part of Bihar. The district headquarters is located in [[Dumra, Sitamarhi|Dumra]], {{convert|5|km|mi|0|spell=in}} south of Sita temple.{{Clarify|reason=the lead says Sitamarhi is the HQ|date=May 2012}}\n\n[[Rama Navami]] is a spring festival in Dumra, widely celebrated with a large fair held to mark the occasion. Also in janki mandir a marriage ceremony of lord ram and sita mata happens every year.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/place/Sitamarhi Sitamarhi], Encyclopedia Britannica (2014), Quote: \"A large Ramanavami fair, celebrating the birth of Lord Rama, is held in spring with considerable trade in pottery, spices, brass ware, and cotton cloth. A cattle fair held in Sitamarhi is the largest in Bihar state. The town is sacred as the birthplace of the goddess Sita (also called Janaki), the wife of Lord Ram.\"</ref> [[Sama Chakeva]] is a prominent winter festival dedicated to celebrate brother-sister relationships.<ref>{{cite web|title=Festivals of Bihar|url=http://gov.bih.nic.in/Profile/festivals.htm|publisher=[[Government of Bihar]]|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> This is a major cultural event with marriage ceremonies and many cultural rituals that take much preparation.<ref>[Mithila kaa Itihas (Hindi Book), Author: Dr. Ram Prakash Sharma, Publisher: Kameshwer Singh Darbhanga Sanskrit University, Darbhanga, Page No.: 460]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSitamarhi, located at {{Coord|26.6|N|85.48|E}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/34/Sitamarhi.html|title=Maps, Weather, and Airports for Sitamarhi, India|website=Fallingrain.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> has an average elevation of {{convert|56|m|ft}}.\n\nThere are multiple small towns that are famous in Sitamarhi, like [[Bairgania]] and Sursand which is located at Indo-Nepal border and is very famous. Few other famous places in Sitamarhi region are Bath Asli , Sonbarsa,Sheohar,Bajpatti,Pupri and Parihar are very good town. Dumra is near Sitamarhi which is known for all the government offices.\n\nRiga village is close to this town and is known for suger mills.\n\n==Demographics==\nSitamarhi city has a total population of around 106,093. There are around 56,693 males, and \n49,400 females. The amount of literate males are 39,537, and the amount of literate females are 29,970. In total 69,507 people are literate. The average literacy rate is 77.03% in total, 81.98% for males, and 71.33% for females. The sexratio is 871. The child sexratio is 872.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census2011.co.in/census/metropolitan/168-sitamarhi.html|title=Sitamarhi District Population Data - Census 2011|website=www.census2011.co.in}}</ref>\n\n=={{anchor|Connectivity}} Transportation==\n[[National Highway 77 (India)|National Highway 77]] connects the area to the [[Muzaffarpur district]] and [[Patna]]. National Highways 77, 104, and other roads connect to the adjoining districts. State highways link it to [[Madhubani district]] in the east and [[Sheohar]] in the west.\n\n[[Sitamarhi Junction railway station]] is a five-platform station on the [[Darbhanga]]\u2013[[Raxaul]]\u2013[[Narkatiaganj]] line, which was converted to broad gauge in February 2014. Another broad-gauge track connects Sitamarhi to [[Muzaffarpur]]. Direct train services are available from Sitamarhi railway junction to places such as New Delhi, Kolkata, Varanasi, Lucknow, Guwahati (Kamakhya), Hyderabad, Kanpur and Mumbai.\n\nThe nearest internationl airport to Sitamarhi is the [[Jay Prakash Narayan International Airport]] which is about {{convert|120|km|mi}} away.\n\nSitamarhi is connected to cities in and around Bihar by state-owned transport services. Many private buses (both AC and non-AC) operate between Sitamarhi and [[Patna]].\n\n==Media==\nSitamarhi has an [[All India Radio]] (AIR) relay station known as Akashvani Sitamarhi, broadcasting on FM frequencies. People from Sitamarhi have developed a news portal [http://Sitamarhi.org Sitamarhi.org]\n\n==Education==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=March 2018}}\nThe following is a partial list of [[schools in Sitamarhi]]\n*[[Front Age, Kiran Chowk]]\n*[[Bharati uchchangle Vidhayalaya Dumra in front of Hawaii field]]\n*[[Gyan Bharati Prepatory School,Purandaha Rajawara ,Sonbarsa Sitamarhi]]*\n*N.S.D.A.V Public school\n* [[Janki Vidya Niketan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janki_Vidya_Niketan |title=Janki Vidya Niketan - Janki Vidya Niketan|publisher=}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=October 2019}}\n* Kendriya Vidyalaya Jawahar Nagar, Sutihara\n* Saraswati Vidya Mandir, Ring bandh\n*[[S.V.Rising Point school ,old Exchange Road mirchaipatti Sitamarhi]]\n*[[Vidya Bharati school,Shantinagar, Sitamarhi. ]]\n* Hellen's School Sitamarhi\n* Delhi Public School, Lagma\n* Brilliant Public School, Sitamarhi\n*[[Mother's Shadow play and Prepatory Public schooy Pilli Kutti Ring bandh Sitamarhi]]\n* R.O.S. Public School, Khairwa, Riga Road, Sitamarhi\n* [[Sacred Heart School, Sitamarhi|Sacred Heart School]]\n* MP High School (Sitamarhi High School, Dumra) Anand Nagar, Talkhapur, Dumra\n* Mathura High School\n* Sri Gandhi High School, Parihar\n* Lakshmi High School\n* Kamala Girls High School\n*[[Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalaya, Sitamarhi|Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalaya Sitamarhi (JNV Sitmarhi)]]\n*Sun Shine Public School- Shantinagar\n*State middle school-sundargama\n*Vidyamandir Classes in Sitamarhi\n*Sushila singha pmky coching center in Virta Tola Punaura\n* Holy faith public high school, old exchange road\n* Genius Global Academy (Baath Asli)\n\n'Hospitals'\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/District Portal of Sitamarhi]\n* [http://tirhut-muzaffarpur.bih.nic.in Official Website of Tirhut Division]\n\n{{Tirhut Division}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Sitamarhi district]]\n[[Category:Sitamarhi district]]\n[[Category:Places in the Ramayana]]\n", "name_user": "TheImaCow", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix another typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sitamarhi"}
