 web | url=http://northfordice.com/Page.asp?n=135338&org=NORTHFORDICE | title=High School Hockey | publisher=Northford Ice Pavilion | accessdate=December 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe arena formerly hosted the [[Connecticut Whale (NWHL)|Connecticut Whale]] of the [[National Women's Hockey League]] in the [[2016\u201317 NWHL season|2016\u201317 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/whale-moves-to-northford-ice-pavilion-for-second-season/n-5137453 |title=Whale Moves to Northford Ice Pavilion for Second Season |publisher=OurSports Central |date=May 5, 2016}}</ref>  It also formerly hosted the [[NCAA Division I]] program of [[Quinnipiac Bobcats men's ice hockey]], in the era before the [[TD Banknorth Sports Center]] was opened.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nhregister.com/colleges/article/Hamden-native-Joe-O-Connor-right-at-home-with-12617745.php | title=Hamden native Joe O\u2019Connor right at home with Quinnipiac hockey team | first=Chip | last=Malafronte | newspaper=New Haven Register | date=February 15, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:NorthfordIcePavilionInterior.jpg|thumb|right|234px|October 2006 men's hockey game at the Pavilion, between the Quinnipiac Bobcats and the [[Robert Morris Colonials]]]]\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|41.3946|-72.8143|display=title}}\n\n{{Connecticut Whale (NWHL)}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct college ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in New Haven County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Whale (NWHL)| ]]\n[[Category:North Branford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:College ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n\n{{Connecticut-stadium-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northford_Ice_Pavilion"}
{"title_page": "LeVar Burton", "text_new": "{{redirect|LeVar|other people with the name|LeVar (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = LeVar Burton\n| image        = LeVar Burton Photo Op GalaxyCon Richmond 2020.jpg\n| caption      = LeVar Burton at [[GalaxyCon]] Richmond in 2020\n| birth_name   = {{nowrap|Levardis Robert Martyn Burton Jr.}}\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1957|2|16}}\n| birth_place  = [[Landstuhl]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], [[West Germany]] (now [[Germany]])\n| citizenship  = [[United States]]\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Southern California]]\n| other_names  = \n| residence    = [[Sherman Oaks, California]], U.S.\n| years_active = 1976\u2013present\n| occupation   = Actor, presenter, director, author\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Stephanie Cozart Burton<br />|1992|}}\n| children     = 2\n| website      = {{url|levarburton.com}}\n| awards       = [[#Awards|See Awards]]\n}}\n\n'''Levardis Robert Martyn Burton Jr.''' (born February 16, 1957) is an American actor, presenter, director, and author. His first major part was the role of a young [[Kunta Kinte]] in the 1977 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television miniseries ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', a role he reprised in the 1988 television film ''[[Roots: The Gift]]''. In 1983 he became the host of the long-running [[PBS]] children's series ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'', and again performed a lead role as Lt. Commander [[Geordi La Forge]] in ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]''. He has also directed a number of television episodes for various iterations of ''[[Star Trek]]'', among other programs.\n\n==Early life==\nBurton was born at the U.S. Army [[Landstuhl Regional Medical Center]] in [[West Germany]]. His mother, Erma Gene (n\u00e9e Christian), was a social worker, administrator, and educator.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/levarburton/status/597417014760644609 |title=Twitter |date=May 10, 2015 |website=Mobile.twitter.com |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> His father, Levardis Robert Martyn Burton, was a photographer for the [[Signal Corps (United States Army)|U.S. Army Signal Corps]] at the time he was stationed at Landstuhl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/26/LeVar-Burton.html |title=LeVar Burton Biography (1957\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=DSNB&d_place=DSNB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F36079871F87D12&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Celebrity Q&A: Burton's Background |date=May 18, 1993 |work=[[The Deseret News]] |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.herald-mail.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=186810&format=html |title=Pennsylvania: Burton speaks of 'Roots,' other strong influences |website=[[The Herald-Mail]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810050237/http://www.herald-mail.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=186810&format=html |archive-date=August 10, 2011 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Burton and his two sisters were raised by his mother in [[Sacramento, California]].<ref name=BurtonSacraised-Sactownmag>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sactownmag.com/February-March-2012/LeVar-Burton-Q-A/ |title=LeVar Burton Q&A |last=Lee |first=Elyssa |date=February\u2013March 2012 |website=Sactown Magazine |access-date=July 20, 2013}}\n*<sup>a</sup> 'You live in LA now, but Sacramento comes up regularly in your tweets.' \"-It's my hometown, my home base. It's where I grew up. I was born in Landstuhl, Germany in '57, came to Sacramento in '59\u2014we lived in Glen Elder\u2014then went back to [Germany] in '64, then [returned to Sacramento] in '66. [Burton's father was a photographer in the Army.] My parents split up during that second tour of duty when I was in the third or fourth grade. So my mom, my sisters and I settled in West Sacramento, in Broderick. Then we moved to South Sacramento when I was in the sixth grade\u2014St. Anne's Elementary.\"</ref>\n\nBurton was raised [[Roman Catholic]] and, at the age of 13, entered St. Pius X Minor Seminary in [[Galt, California]], to become a priest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22215472.html |title=LeVar Burton At Book-Signing: Actor, Now Author, Returns To Sacramento |date=February 19, 1997 |website=[[The Sacramento Observer]] |publisher=Highbeam.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810113128/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22215472.html |archive-date=August 10, 2011 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://fox40.com/2016/11/21/remake-of-roots-now-streaming-on-hulu/ |title=Remake of 'Roots' Now Streaming on Hulu |date=November 21, 2016 |publisher=[[KTXL]] News |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> While in seminary, he read works by the philosophers [[Laozi]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], and [[S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard]], which caused him to question the Catholic dogma that Catholicism is the only true religion.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/person/levar-burton |title=Metacritic.com |publisher=Metacritic.com |access-date=January 8, 2014}}</ref> At seventeen, Burton graduated with the class of 1974 and enrolled at the [[University of Southern California]] with a drama scholarship.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/levar-burton-538182?page=2 |title=LeVar Burton |date=February 16, 1957 |publisher=Biography.com |access-date=January 8, 2014}}</ref> While at the University of Southern California, Burton was a member of the [[Sigma Alpha Mu]] fraternity. He graduated from the University of Southern California's School of Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dramaticarts.usc.edu/alumni/ |title=Alumni |publisher=USC School of Dramatic Arts |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425115007/http://dramaticarts.usc.edu/alumni/ |archive-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nBurton first appeared on television in a drama about a misunderstood deaf boy.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} He made his film acting debut in 1977 when he played the young [[Kunta Kinte]] in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] miniseries ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', based on the [[Roots: The Saga of an American Family|novel of the same name]] by [[Alex Haley]]. Burton's audition for the role of Kunta was the first of his professional career.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} As a result of his performance, he was nominated for the Emmy for Best Actor in a Drama Series. Burton reprised the role of Kunta Kinte in the 1988 television film ''[[Roots: The Gift]]''. When asked about the societal influence of ''Roots'', Burton is quoted as saying, \"It expanded the consciousness of people. Blacks and whites began to see each other as human beings, not as stereotypes. And if you throw a pebble into the pond, you're going to get ripples. I think the only constant is change, and it's always slow. Anything that happens overnight is lacking in foundation. ''Roots'' is part of a changing trend, and it's still being played out.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Beale |first=Lewis |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/access/87945887.html?dids=87945887:87945887&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+29%2C+1987&author=LEWIS+BEALE%2C+Los+Angeles+Daily+News&pub=South+Florida+Sun+-+Sentinel&desc=RESEARCHING+TV%27S+%60ROOTS%27+A+DECADE+LATER&pqatl=google |title=Researching TV's Roots a Decade Later |date=January 29, 1987 |work=Ft. Lauderdale [[Sun Sentinel]] |access-date=February 26, 2011 |publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com}}</ref>\n\nBurton played a role as a visitor to ''[[Fantasy Island]]'', was a participant in ''[[Battle of the Network Stars]]'', a guest of the ''[[Muppet Show]]''{{'}}s televised premiere party for the release of ''[[The Muppet Movie]]'', and a frequent guest on several game shows. In 1986, he appeared in the music video for the song \"[[Word Up! (song)|Word Up!]]\" by the [[funk]]/[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] group [[Cameo (band)|Cameo]].\n\nBurton accepted an invitation to host ''[[Rebop (TV)|Rebop]]'', a multicultural series designed for young people ages 9\u201315, produced by WGBH for [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].\n\n===''Reading Rainbow''===\nBurton was the host and executive producer of ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'' starting in 1983 for [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jones |first=Fred |title=Learning to Read the Rainbow |date=May 19, 1999 |work=Tacoma Herald}}</ref> The series ran for 23 seasons, making it one of the longest-running children's programs on the network. The series garnered over 200 broadcast awards over its run, including a [[Peabody Award]] and 26 [[Emmy Award]]s, 11 of which were in the Outstanding Children's Series category.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0085075/awards |title=Reading Rainbow Awards |publisher=IMDb.com |access-date=June 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rrkidz.com/about-us |title=About Us \u2013 Reading Rainbow |website=Rrkidz.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624211807/http://www.rrkidz.com/about-us |archive-date=June 24, 2012 |access-date=June 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Burton himself won 12 Emmy awards as host and producer of the show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000996/awards |title=LeVar Burton Awards |publisher=IMDb.com |access-date=June 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Reading Rainbow'' went off the air in 2006, Burton and his business partner, Mark Wolfe, acquired the global rights to the brand and formed RRKIDZ, a new media company for children. '' Reading Rainbow'' was reimagined as an all new application for the iPad in 2012, and was an immediate success, becoming the number-one educational application within 36 hours. At RRKIDZ, Burton serves as co-founder and curator-in-chief, ensuring that the projects produced under the banner meet the high expectations and trust of the ''Reading Rainbow'' brand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rrkidz.com/team |title=Reading Rainbow Team |website=Rrkidz.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130628195413/http://www.rrkidz.com/team |archive-date=June 28, 2013 |access-date=June 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2014, Burton and numerous coworkers from other past works started a [[Kickstarter]] campaign project to bring back ''Reading Rainbow''. To keep with the changing formats to which young children are exposed, his efforts are being directed at making this new program web based, following the success of the tablet application he helped create in recent years. His desire is to have the new ''Reading Rainbow'' be integrated into the classrooms of elementary schools across the country, and for schools in need to have free access.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Burton Calls On 'Star Trek' Fans To Bring 'Reading Rainbow' To The Next Generation |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/28/316715135/burton-calls-on-star-trek-fans-to-bring-reading-rainbow-to-the-next-generation |series=[[All Things Considered]] |network=[[NPR]] |date=May 28, 2014 |credits=Presenter: [[Melissa Block]]}}</ref> The Kickstarter campaign has since raised over $5 million, reaching triple its goal in only three days.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/readingrainbow/bring-reading-rainbow-back-for-every-child-everywh/ |title=Bring Reading Rainbow Back for Every Child, Everywhere! by LeVar Burton & Reading Rainbow \u2014 Kickstarter |website=[[Kickstarter]] |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, LeVar Burton was sued by the public broadcasting company [[WNED-TV]] for alleged copyright infringement for use of the Reading Rainbow brand in marketing the new iPad app and other online media.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/reading-rainbow-owner-accuses-levar-burton-theft-extortion-lawsuit-1027372 |title='Reading Rainbow' Owner Accuses LeVar Burton of \"Theft and Extortion\" in Lawsuit |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref> RRKIDZ is now known as LeVar Burton Kids and the iPad app is now called Skybrary.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.levarburtonkids.com/skybrary |title=Welcome to Skybrary! {{!}} LeVar Burton Kids |website=[[LeVar Burton Kids]] |access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''Star Trek: The Next Generation''===\nIn 1986, [[Gene Roddenberry]] approached Burton with the role of the then Lieutenant Junior Grade [[Geordi La Forge]] in the ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'' television series. The character is [[blindness|blind]] but is granted \"sight\" through the use of a prosthetic device called a [[VISOR]] worn over his eyes. La Forge started out serving as the [[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701-D)|USS ''Enterprise'']]'s [[helmsman]], and as of the show's second season, had become its chief engineer. At the time, Burton was considerably better known than [[Patrick Stewart]] in the United States, due to his roles in ''Roots'' and ''Reading Rainbow''. When the show premiered, the [[Associated Press]] stated that Burton's role was essentially the \"new [[Spock]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Dg0VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8wIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5563,4967413&dq=levar+burton+spock&hl=en |title=LeVar Burton Cast As The Spock of TV's New 'Star Trek' |date=August 2, 1987 |website=[[The Blade (Toledo, Ohio)]] |access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref> In a 2019 interview, Burton laughed in disbelief at the idea, stating \"that speculation never came to fruition.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Loughlin |first=Ryan |url=https://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/attheshore/events/oc-con-returns-to-the-music-pier-with-special-guest/article_3cab02bf-57f9-5145-ad15-4bb875e5df85.html |title=OC Con returns to the music pier with special guest LeVar Burton |date=2019-04-02 |work=Press of Atlantic City |access-date=2019-06-13 |last2=Cronik |first2=Scott |location=Atlantic City, NJ}}</ref>\n\nBurton also portrayed La Forge in the subsequent feature films based on ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'', beginning with ''[[Star Trek Generations]]'' (1994) through to ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis]]'' (2002).\n\nHe directed two episodes of ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'', several episodes of ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'' and ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]''.\n\n===Other appearances===\n[[File:Tipper Gore.jpg|thumb|250px|Burton with [[social activist]] and former [[Second Lady of the United States|Second Lady]] [[Tipper Gore]]]]\nOn television, Burton has helped dramatize the last days of [[Jim Jones]]'s suicide cult in [[Guyana]], the life and times of [[Jesse Owens]], and the life of the nine-year-old [[Booker T. Washington]]. He portrayed [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] in the 2001 film ''[[Ali (film)|Ali]]''. He also portrayed [[Detroit Tigers|Detroit Tiger]] [[Ron LeFlore]] in the television movie ''One in a Million, The Ron LeFlore Story''.\n\nIn 1987, Burton played Dave Robinson, a journalist (sports writer), in the third season of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', episode 16 \u2013 \"Death Takes a Dive\", starring [[Angela Lansbury]] as [[Jessica Fletcher]].\n\nIn 1992, a clip of Burton's voice was [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] by [[DC Talk]] for the track \"Time is...\" on their album ''[[Free at Last (DC Talk album)|Free at Last]]''. The sample is at the very end of the song, in which Burton can be heard saying: \"Whoa, wait a minute.\"\nHe has also lent his voice to several animated projects, including Kwame in the cartoon series ''[[Captain Planet and the Planeteers]]'' (1990\u20131993) and ''[[The New Adventures of Captain Planet]]'' (1993\u20131996), ''[[Family Guy]]'', ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]'' and ''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]''. Burton is on the audio version of ''[[The Watsons Go to Birmingham: 1963]]'' by [[Christopher Paul Curtis]]. Burton has been cast as voice actor for ''[[Black Lightning]]'' in ''[[Superman/Batman: Public Enemies]]'' DVD.\n\nBurton appeared several times as a celebrity guest on the [[Dick Clark]]-hosted ''[[Pyramid (game show)|$25,000 and $100,000 Pyramids]]'', from 1982 until 1988. Burton also was the strongest link in the special ''Star Trek'' episode of ''[[The Weakest Link]]''. He defeated his final opponent [[Robert Picardo]] and won $167,500 for his charity, Junior Achievement of Southern California, a record for the show at that time and the largest amount won in any Celebrity Edition of the show (it was later surpassed by a $188,500 win in a \"Tournament of Losers\" episode).\n\nHe has made appearances in such sitcoms as ''[[Becker (TV series)|Becker]]''.\n\n[[File:Levar burton.jpg|thumb|left|Burton at the Schlow Centre Region Library, January 29, 2007]]\nBurton is the host and executive producer of a [[Documentary film|documentary]] titled ''The Science of Peace'', which was in production as of 2007. It investigates the science and technology aimed at enabling [[world peace]], sometimes called [[peace science]]. The film explores some of the concepts of shared [[Noetic theory|noetic]] consciousness, having been sponsored in part by the [[Institute of Noetic Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scienceofpeace.com/document.html |title=Science of Peace |website=scienceofpeace.com}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in an April Fool's episode of ''[[Smosh]]'' pretending to have taken over the channel and making various edits at popular Smosh videos.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rz5IlodOKE8 |title=LeVar Burton Buys Smosh (April Fools) |publisher=YouTube |access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe makes occasional appearances on ''[[This Week in Tech]]'', where he is a self-proclaimed \"nerd\", and also participated in the [[Consumer Electronics Show]] 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hackaday.com/2010/01/09/ces-famous-people-at-ces/cimg0987/ |title=James and Levar Burton |date=January 9, 2010 |website=Hackaday.com |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he made an appearance on ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!]]'' as the ghost of himself in the episode \"Greene Machine\".\n\nIn February 2011, Burton made an appearance as himself on NBC's ''[[Community (TV Series)|Community]]'' in the episodes [[Intermediate Documentary Filmmaking]] and [[Geothermal Escapism]].\n\nBurton has appeared as a fictionalized, humorous version of himself on ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'', first appearing in the episode \"[[The Toast Derivation]]\", in which he almost attends a party thrown by Sheldon (before swearing off Twitter), in November 2012 in the episode \"[[The Habitation Configuration]]\", in which he appears on \"Fun With Flags\" in exchange for lunch and gas money, and again in the November 2014 episode \"[[The Champagne Reflection]]\", in which he returns for the 232nd episode of \"Fun With Flags\" in exchange for Sheldon deleting his contact details.\n\nIn 2012, he had a recurring role as dean Paul Haley on the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] series [[Perception (U.S. TV series)|''Perception'']]. For the second season (2013), he became part of the regular cast.\n\nIn 2014, he had a guest appearance in an introduction section for the 200th episode of Achievement Hunter's show, ''Achievement Hunter Weekly Update'' (AHWU). In May 2014, he appeared as a guest on the [[YouTube]] channel [[SciShow]], explaining the science behind [[Double rainbow|double]], [[Tertiary rainbow|tertiary]], and [[Quaternary rainbow|quaternary]] rainbows. Late in 2014, he had another guest appearance on a 24-hour Extra Life, a fundraising organization for Children's Miracle Network hospitals, stream by [[Rooster Teeth]]. Burton has also taped a [[recycling]] field trip for YouTube.\n\nIn 2017, Burton began a podcast titled \"LeVar Burton Reads\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nerdist.com/levar-burtons-new-podcast-is-like-reading-rainbow-for-adults/ |title=LeVar Burton's New Podcast is Like Reading Rainbow for Adults |last=Ratcliffe |first=Amy |date=June 28, 2017 |publisher=Nerdist}}</ref> Each episode features Burton reading a short story.\n\n===Directing===\nThroughout the 1990s and early 2000s, Burton directed episodes for each of the various ''Star Trek'' series then in production. He has directed more ''Star Trek'' episodes than any other former regular cast member.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000996/ |title=LeVar Burton |website=IMDb |access-date=April 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has also directed episodes of ''[[Charmed]]'', ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'', ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]'', and ''[[Soul Food (TV series)|Soul Food: The Series]]'', as well as the miniseries ''[[Miracle's Boys]]'' and the biopic ''[[The Tiger Woods Story]]''. He also directed the 1999 [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] ''[[Smart House (film)|Smart House]]'' starring [[Katey Sagal]], [[Kevin Kilner]] and [[Jessica Steen]].\n\nHis first theatrical film direction was ''[[Blizzard (film)|Blizzard]]'' (2003), for which he received a \"Best of Fest\" award from the [[Chicago International Children's Film Festival]], and a [[Genie Award]] nomination for his work on the film's theme song, \"Center of My Heart\".\n\nBurton is on the board of directors for the [[Directors Guild of America]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLeVar Burton married Stephanie Cozart-Burton,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://matineeclassics.com/celebrities/actors/levar_burton/details/ |title=Matinee Classics |date=February 16, 1957 |publisher=Matinee Classics |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216062001/http://matineeclassics.com/celebrities/actors/levar_burton/details/ |archive-date=December 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> a professional make-up artist, in 1992. He and his wife currently live in [[Sherman Oaks]], California.<ref name=\"Bio\" />  LeVar Burton has two children, a daughter Michaela \"Mica\" with his wife, and a son, Eian Burton (born 1980) from a previous relationship.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/02/02/Actor-Levar-Burton-has-paid-8863-in-overdue-child/5831444546000/ |title=Actor Levar Burton has paid $8,863 in overdue child... |date=February 2, 1984 |publisher=United Press International}}</ref> Mica was an employee of [[Rooster Teeth]]'s news division, The Know.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theknow.roosterteeth.com/ |title=The Know |website=theknow.roosterteeth.com}}</ref>\nBurton is also a fan of [[Soccer|English football]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/levarburton/status/854057675327287297 |title=Levar Burton |website=Twitter.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/levarburton/status/854069154982182912 |title=Levar Burton |website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\nAlthough raised Catholic and at one point studying to become a priest,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2018/11/levar-burton-skeleton/566489/ |title=LeVar Burton on Pursuing the Priesthood Before Acting |last=Fadulu |first=Lola |date=2018-11-07 |website=The Atlantic |language=en-US |access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> Burton no longer identifies with any religion, saying: \"I walked away from the seminary, I walked away from Catholicism, I walked away from organized religion because I felt that there was more for me to explore in the world, and that I could do that without adhering to one specific belief system or another.\"<ref>{{Cite podcast |url=http://www.levarburtonpodcast.com |title=Episode 15: \"Unassigned Territory\" by Stephanie Powell Watts |website=Levar Burton Reads |host=Levar Burton |date=January 30, 2018 |time=38:52 |access-date=November 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Burton joined the board of directors for the [[AIDS Research Alliance]], a non-profit, medical research organization dedicated to finding a cure for AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pr.com/press-release/436088 |title=Emmy Award Winner LeVar Burton Joins AIDS Research Alliance's Board of Directors |date=September 11, 2012 |publisher=AIDS Research Alliance |access-date=June 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Burton was one of the five inaugural honorees to the Sacramento Walk of Stars.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sacramentowalkofstars.com/ |title=Sacramento Walk of Stars |last=<!--Not stated--> |date=2016 |website=sacramentowalkofstars.com |publisher=Sacramento Walk of Stars |access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> In 2019, Sacramento named LeVar Burton Park in his honor. The park is located in the Meadowview neighborhood, down the street from the house where Burton and his sisters grew up.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/585499/sacramento-park-renamed-after-levar-burton-reading-rainbow |title=Sacramento Has Renamed a Local Park After Reading Rainbow Host LeVar Burton |last=Rossen |first=Jake |date=2019-06-12 |website=MentalFloss.Com |publisher=Mental Floss |access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{main|LeVar Burton filmography}}\n\n==Awards and honors==\n===Awards===\n{{More citations needed|section|date=February 2019}}\n\n====Nominations====\n* 1977 \u2013 [[Emmy]] \u2013 Outstanding Lead Actor for a Single Performance in a Drama or Comedy Series \u2013 ''Roots'' (Part 1, \"Kunta Kinte\")\n* 1998, 2001, 2005 \u2013 [[Image Awards]] variously for Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series and Outstanding Youth or Children's Series/Special \u2014 ''Reading Rainbow'' (both as Self and as Executive Producer)\n* 1991, 1992, 1994, 1995, 1999 \u2013 [[Daytime Emmy]] \u2013 Outstanding Children's Series \u2013 ''Reading Rainbow'' (Executive Producer)\n* 1985, 1986, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2003, 2005, 2006, 2007 \u2013 Daytime Emmy \u2013 Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series \u2014 ''Reading Rainbow'' (Self)\n* 2004 \u2013 [[Genie Award]] \u2013 Best Achievement in Music-Original Song \u2013 ''Blizzard'' (Co-composer \"Center of My Heart\")\n* 2006 \u2013 [[Black Reel Award]] \u2013 Best Director-Television \u2013 ''Miracle's Boys''\n\n====Wins====\n* 1990 \u2013 Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7030 Hollywood Blvd. ''for television achievement''\n* 1992 \u2013 [[Peabody Award]] \u2013 ''Reading Rainbow'' (as executive producer of episode, \"The Wall\")\n* 1994, 1996, 1999, 2002, 2003 \u2013 [[Image Award]] \u2013 ''variously for'' Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series and Outstanding Youth or Children's Series/Special \u2013 ''Reading Rainbow'' (both as Self and as Executive Producer)\n* 2000 \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album]] \u2013 ''The Autobiography of Martin Luther King Jr.''\n* 1990, 1993, 1996, 1997, 1998, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2005, 2007 \u2013 Daytime Emmy \u2013 [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Children's Series|Outstanding Children's Series]] \u2013 ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'' (Executive Producer)\n* 2001, 2002 \u2013 Daytime Emmy \u2013  [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in Children's Programming|Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series]] \u2013 ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'' (Self)\n* 2003 \u2013 [[TCA Awards|Television Critics Association Award]] \u2013 Outstanding Achievement in Children's Programming \u2013 ''Reading Rainbow'' (Executive Producer)\n* 2004 \u2013 [[Chicago International Children's Film Festival]] \u2013 Best of Fest \u2013 ''Blizzard'' (Director)\n\n===Honors===\n* 2019: [[Case Western Reserve University]]'s [[Inamori Ethics Prize]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dawidziak |first=Mark |url=https://www.cleveland.com/entertainment/2019/09/levar-burton-receiving-case-western-reserve-universitys-inamori-ethics-prize.html |title=LeVar Burton receiving Case Western Reserve University's Inamori Ethics Prize |date=September 13, 2019 |work=[[The Plain Dealer#cleveland.com|Cleveland.com]] |access-date=September 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919033826/https://www.cleveland.com/entertainment/2019/09/levar-burton-receiving-case-western-reserve-universitys-inamori-ethics-prize.html |archive-date=September 19, 2019 |publisher=[[Advance Publications]] |location=[[Cleveland]] |author-link=Mark Dawidziak}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://observer.case.edu/2019-inamori-ethics-prize-winner-levar-burton-speaks-but-also-listens/ |title=2019 Inamori Ethics Prize winner LeVar Burton speaks and listens |last=Hooke |first=Matt |website=The Observer |access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''Aftermath'', 1997, {{ISBN|0-446-67960-7}}\n* ''The Rhino Who Swallowed a Storm'', 2014, {{ISBN|0-990-53950-4}}\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal inline|Speculative fiction}}\n* {{Portal inline|Television}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Nishikawa, Kinohi. \"LeVar Burton\". ''The Greenwood Encyclopedia of African American Literature''. Ed. Hans Ostrom and J. David Macey Jr., 5 vols. Westport, CT: Greenwood Press, 2005. 219.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.levarburton.com/}}\n* [http://www.rrkidz.com/team/ RRKIDZ (Reading Rainbow) \u2013 LeVar Burton, Co-Founder, Curator-in-Chief]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130415043932/http://www.burtonwolfeentertainment.com/ Burton / Wolfe Entertainment] (production company)\n* {{IMDb name|0000996|LeVar Burton}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Allmovie name|9812|LeVar Burton}}\n* {{emmytvlegends name|levar-burton|LeVar Burton}}\n\n{{LeVar Burton}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for LeVar Burton\n| list =\n{{Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in Children's Programming}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album 2000s}}\n{{NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{#related:Kunta Kinte}}\n{{#related:Geordi La Forge}}\n{{#related:Reading Rainbow}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burton, Levar}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American television directors]]\n[[Category:African-American television personalities]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Male actors from California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:PBS people]]\n[[Category:Reading Rainbow]]\n[[Category:USC School of Dramatic Arts alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{redirect|LeVar|other people with the name|LeVar (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = LeVar Burton\n| image        = LeVar Burton Photo Op GalaxyCon Richmond 2020.jpg\n| caption      = LeVar Burton at [[GalaxyCon]] Richmond in 2020\n| birth_name   = {{nowrap|Levardis Robert Martyn Burton Jr.}}\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1957|2|16}}\n| birth_place  = [[Landstuhl]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], [[West Germany]] (now [[Germany]])\n| citizenship  = [[United States]]\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Southern California]]\n| other_names  = \n| residence    = [[Sherman Oaks, California]], U.S.\n| years_active = 1976\u2013present\n| occupation   = Actor, presenter, director, author\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Stephanie Cozart Burton<br />|1992|}}\n| children     = 2\n| website      = {{url|levarburton.com}}\n| awards       = [[#Awards|See Awards]]\n}}\n\n'''Levardis Robert Martyn Burton Jr.''' (born February 16, 1957) is an American actor, presenter, director, and author. His first major part was the role of a young [[Kunta Kinte]] in the 1977 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television miniseries ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', a role he reprised in the 1988 television film ''[[Roots: The Gift]]''. In 1983 he became the host of the long-running [[PBS]] children's series ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'', and again performed a lead role as Lt. Commander [[Geordi La Forge]] in ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]''. He has also directed a number of television episodes for various iterations of ''[[Star Trek]]'', among other programs.\n\n==Early life==\nBurton was born at the U.S. Army [[Landstuhl Regional Medical Center]] in [[West Germany]]. His mother, Erma Gene (n\u00e9e Christian), was a social worker, administrator, and educator.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/levarburton/status/597417014760644609 |title=Twitter |date=May 10, 2015 |website=Mobile.twitter.com |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> His father, Levardis Robert Martyn Burton, was a photographer for the [[Signal Corps (United States Army)|U.S. Army Signal Corps]] at the time he was stationed at Landstuhl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/26/LeVar-Burton.html |title=LeVar Burton Biography (1957\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=DSNB&d_place=DSNB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F36079871F87D12&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Celebrity Q&A: Burton's Background |date=May 18, 1993 |work=[[The Deseret News]] |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.herald-mail.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=186810&format=html |title=Pennsylvania: Burton speaks of 'Roots,' other strong influences |website=[[The Herald-Mail]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810050237/http://www.herald-mail.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=186810&format=html |archive-date=August 10, 2011 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Burton and his two sisters were raised by his mother in [[Sacramento, California]].<ref name=BurtonSacraised-Sactownmag>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sactownmag.com/February-March-2012/LeVar-Burton-Q-A/ |title=LeVar Burton Q&A |last=Lee |first=Elyssa |date=February\u2013March 2012 |website=Sactown Magazine |access-date=July 20, 2013}}\n*<sup>a</sup> 'You live in LA now, but Sacramento comes up regularly in your tweets.' \"-It's my hometown, my home base. It's where I grew up. I was born in Landstuhl, Germany in '57, came to Sacramento in '59\u2014we lived in Glen Elder\u2014then went back to [Germany] in '64, then [returned to Sacramento] in '66. [Burton's father was a photographer in the Army.] My parents split up during that second tour of duty when I was in the third or fourth grade. So my mom, my sisters and I settled in West Sacramento, in Broderick. Then we moved to South Sacramento when I was in the sixth grade\u2014St. Anne's Elementary.\"</ref>\n\nBurton was raised [[Roman Catholic]] and, at the age of 13, entered St. Pius X Minor Seminary in [[Galt, California]], to become a priest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22215472.html |title=LeVar Burton At Book-Signing: Actor, Now Author, Returns To Sacramento |date=February 19, 1997 |website=[[The Sacramento Observer]] |publisher=Highbeam.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810113128/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22215472.html |archive-date=August 10, 2011 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://fox40.com/2016/11/21/remake-of-roots-now-streaming-on-hulu/ |title=Remake of 'Roots' Now Streaming on Hulu |date=November 21, 2016 |publisher=[[KTXL]] News |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> While in seminary, he read works by the philosophers [[Laozi]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], and [[S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard]], which caused him to question the Catholic dogma that Catholicism is the only true religion.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/person/levar-burton |title=Metacritic.com |publisher=Metacritic.com |access-date=January 8, 2014}}</ref> At seventeen, Burton graduated with the class of 1974 and enrolled at the [[University of Southern California]] with a drama scholarship.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/levar-burton-538182?page=2 |title=LeVar Burton |date=February 16, 1957 |publisher=Biography.com |access-date=January 8, 2014}}</ref> While at the University of Southern California, Burton was a member of the [[Sigma Alpha Mu]] fraternity. He graduated from the University of Southern California's School of Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dramaticarts.usc.edu/alumni/ |title=Alumni |publisher=USC School of Dramatic Arts |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425115007/http://dramaticarts.usc.edu/alumni/ |archive-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nBurton first appeared on television in a drama about a misunderstood deaf boy.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} He made his film acting debut in 1977 when he played the young [[Kunta Kinte]] in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] miniseries ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', based on the [[Roots: The Saga of an American Family|novel of the same name]] by [[Alex Haley]]. Burton's audition for the role of Kunta was the first of his professional career.{{cn|date=December 2019}} As a result of his performance, he was nominated for the Emmy for Best Actor in a Drama Series. Burton reprised the role of Kunta Kinte in the 1988 television film ''[[Roots: The Gift]]''. When asked about the societal influence of ''Roots'', Burton is quoted as saying, \"It expanded the consciousness of people. Blacks and whites began to see each other as human beings, not as stereotypes. And if you throw a pebble into the pond, you're going to get ripples. I think the only constant is change, and it's always slow. Anything that happens overnight is lacking in foundation. ''Roots'' is part of a changing trend, and it's still being played out.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Beale |first=Lewis |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/access/87945887.html?dids=87945887:87945887&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+29%2C+1987&author=LEWIS+BEALE%2C+Los+Angeles+Daily+News&pub=South+Florida+Sun+-+Sentinel&desc=RESEARCHING+TV%27S+%60ROOTS%27+A+DECADE+LATER&pqatl=google |title=Researching TV's Roots a Decade Later |date=January 29, 1987 |work=Ft. Lauderdale [[Sun Sentinel]] |access-date=February 26, 2011 |publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com}}</ref>\n\nBurton played a role as a visitor to ''[[Fantasy Island]]'', was a participant in ''[[Battle of the Network Stars]]'', a guest of the ''[[Muppet Show]]''{{'}}s televised premiere party for the release of ''[[The Muppet Movie]]'', and a frequent guest on several game shows. In 1986, he appeared in the music video for the song \"[[Word Up! (song)|Word Up!]]\" by the [[funk]]/[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] group [[Cameo (band)|Cameo]].\n\nBurton accepted an invitation to host ''[[Rebop (TV)|Rebop]]'', a multicultural series designed for young people ages 9\u201315, produced by WGBH for [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].\n\n===''Reading Rainbow''===\nBurton was the host and executive producer of ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'' starting in 1983 for [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jones |first=Fred |title=Learning to Read the Rainbow |date=May 19, 1999 |work=Tacoma Herald}}</ref> The series ran for 23 seasons, making it one of the longest-running children's programs on the network. The series garnered over 200 broadcast awards over its run, including a [[Peabody Award]] and 26 [[Emmy Award]]s, 11 of which were in the Outstanding Children's Series category.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0085075/awards |title=Reading Rainbow Awards |publisher=IMDb.com |access-date=June 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rrkidz.com/about-us |title=About Us \u2013 Reading Rainbow |website=Rrkidz.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624211807/http://www.rrkidz.com/about-us |archive-date=June 24, 2012 |access-date=June 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Burton himself won 12 Emmy awards as host and producer of the show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000996/awards |title=LeVar Burton Awards |publisher=IMDb.com |access-date=June 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Reading Rainbow'' went off the air in 2006, Burton and his business partner, Mark Wolfe, acquired the global rights to the brand and formed RRKIDZ, a new media company for children. '' Reading Rainbow'' was reimagined as an all new application for the iPad in 2012, and was an immediate success, becoming the number-one educational application within 36 hours. At RRKIDZ, Burton serves as co-founder and curator-in-chief, ensuring that the projects produced under the banner meet the high expectations and trust of the ''Reading Rainbow'' brand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rrkidz.com/team |title=Reading Rainbow Team |website=Rrkidz.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130628195413/http://www.rrkidz.com/team |archive-date=June 28, 2013 |access-date=June 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 28, 2014, Burton and numerous coworkers from other past works started a [[Kickstarter]] campaign project to bring back ''Reading Rainbow''. To keep with the changing formats to which young children are exposed, his efforts are being directed at making this new program web based, following the success of the tablet application he helped create in recent years. His desire is to have the new ''Reading Rainbow'' be integrated into the classrooms of elementary schools across the country, and for schools in need to have free access.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Burton Calls On 'Star Trek' Fans To Bring 'Reading Rainbow' To The Next Generation |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/05/28/316715135/burton-calls-on-star-trek-fans-to-bring-reading-rainbow-to-the-next-generation |series=[[All Things Considered]] |network=[[NPR]] |date=May 28, 2014 |credits=Presenter: [[Melissa Block]]}}</ref> The Kickstarter campaign has since raised over $5 million, reaching triple its goal in only three days.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/readingrainbow/bring-reading-rainbow-back-for-every-child-everywh/ |title=Bring Reading Rainbow Back for Every Child, Everywhere! by LeVar Burton & Reading Rainbow \u2014 Kickstarter |website=[[Kickstarter]] |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, LeVar Burton was sued by the public broadcasting company [[WNED-TV]] for alleged copyright infringement for use of the Reading Rainbow brand in marketing the new iPad app and other online media.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/reading-rainbow-owner-accuses-levar-burton-theft-extortion-lawsuit-1027372 |title='Reading Rainbow' Owner Accuses LeVar Burton of \"Theft and Extortion\" in Lawsuit |website=[[Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref> RRKIDZ is now known as LeVar Burton Kids and the iPad app is now called Skybrary.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.levarburtonkids.com/skybrary |title=Welcome to Skybrary! {{!}} LeVar Burton Kids |website=[[LeVar Burton Kids]] |access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''Star Trek: The Next Generation''===\nIn 1986, [[Gene Roddenberry]] approached Burton with the role of the then Lieutenant Junior Grade [[Geordi La Forge]] in the ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'' television series. The character is [[blindness|blind]] but is granted \"sight\" through the use of a prosthetic device called a [[VISOR]] worn over his eyes. La Forge started out serving as the [[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701-D)|USS ''Enterprise'']]'s [[helmsman]], and as of the show's second season, had become its chief engineer. At the time, Burton was considerably better known than [[Patrick Stewart]] in the United States, due to his roles in ''Roots'' and ''Reading Rainbow''. When the show premiered, the [[Associated Press]] stated that Burton's role was essentially the \"new [[Spock]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Dg0VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8wIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5563,4967413&dq=levar+burton+spock&hl=en |title=LeVar Burton Cast As The Spock of TV's New 'Star Trek' |date=August 2, 1987 |website=[[The Blade (Toledo, Ohio)]] |access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref> In a 2019 interview, Burton laughed in disbelief at the idea, stating \"that speculation never came to fruition.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Loughlin |first=Ryan |url=https://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/attheshore/events/oc-con-returns-to-the-music-pier-with-special-guest/article_3cab02bf-57f9-5145-ad15-4bb875e5df85.html |title=OC Con returns to the music pier with special guest LeVar Burton |date=2019-04-02 |work=Press of Atlantic City |access-date=2019-06-13 |last2=Cronik |first2=Scott |location=Atlantic City, NJ}}</ref>\n\nBurton also portrayed La Forge in the subsequent feature films based on ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'', beginning with ''[[Star Trek Generations]]'' (1994) through to ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis]]'' (2002).\n\nHe directed two episodes of ''Star Trek: The Next Generation'', several episodes of ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'' and ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]''.\n\n===Other appearances===\n[[File:Tipper Gore.jpg|thumb|250px|Burton with [[social activist]] and former [[Second Lady of the United States|Second Lady]] [[Tipper Gore]]]]\nOn television, Burton has helped dramatize the last days of [[Jim Jones]]'s suicide cult in [[Guyana]], the life and times of [[Jesse Owens]], and the life of the nine-year-old [[Booker T. Washington]]. He portrayed [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] in the 2001 film ''[[Ali (film)|Ali]]''. He also portrayed [[Detroit Tigers|Detroit Tiger]] [[Ron LeFlore]] in the television movie ''One in a Million, The Ron LeFlore Story''.\n\nIn 1987, Burton played Dave Robinson, a journalist (sports writer), in the third season of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', episode 16 \u2013 \"Death Takes a Dive\", starring [[Angela Lansbury]] as [[Jessica Fletcher]].\n\nIn 1992, a clip of Burton's voice was [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] by [[DC Talk]] for the track \"Time is...\" on their album ''[[Free at Last (DC Talk album)|Free at Last]]''. The sample is at the very end of the song, in which Burton can be heard saying: \"Whoa, wait a minute.\"\nHe has also lent his voice to several animated projects, including Kwame in the cartoon series ''[[Captain Planet and the Planeteers]]'' (1990\u20131993) and ''[[The New Adventures of Captain Planet]]'' (1993\u20131996), ''[[Family Guy]]'', ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]'' and ''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]''. Burton is on the audio version of ''[[The Watsons Go to Birmingham: 1963]]'' by [[Christopher Paul Curtis]]. Burton has been cast as voice actor for ''[[Black Lightning]]'' in ''[[Superman/Batman: Public Enemies]]'' DVD.\n\nBurton appeared several times as a celebrity guest on the [[Dick Clark]]-hosted ''[[Pyramid (game show)|$25,000 and $100,000 Pyramids]]'', from 1982 until 1988. Burton also was the strongest link in the special ''Star Trek'' episode of ''[[The Weakest Link]]''. He defeated his final opponent [[Robert Picardo]] and won $167,500 for his charity, Junior Achievement of Southern California, a record for the show at that time and the largest amount won in any Celebrity Edition of the show (it was later surpassed by a $188,500 win in a \"Tournament of Losers\" episode).\n\nHe has made appearances in such sitcoms as ''[[Becker (TV series)|Becker]]''.\n\n[[File:Levar burton.jpg|thumb|left|Burton at the Schlow Centre Region Library, January 29, 2007]]\nBurton is the host and executive producer of a [[Documentary film|documentary]] titled ''The Science of Peace'', which was in production as of 2007. It investigates the science and technology aimed at enabling [[world peace]], sometimes called [[peace science]]. The film explores some of the concepts of shared [[Noetic theory|noetic]] consciousness, having been sponsored in part by the [[Institute of Noetic Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scienceofpeace.com/document.html |title=Science of Peace |website=scienceofpeace.com}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared in an April Fool's episode of ''[[Smosh]]'' pretending to have taken over the channel and making various edits at popular Smosh videos.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rz5IlodOKE8 |title=LeVar Burton Buys Smosh (April Fools) |publisher=YouTube |access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe makes occasional appearances on ''[[This Week in Tech]]'', where he is a self-proclaimed \"nerd\", and also participated in the [[Consumer Electronics Show]] 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hackaday.com/2010/01/09/ces-famous-people-at-ces/cimg0987/ |title=James and Levar Burton |date=January 9, 2010 |website=Hackaday.com |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he made an appearance on ''[[Tim and Eric Awesome Show, Great Job!]]'' as the ghost of himself in the episode \"Greene Machine\".\n\nIn February 2011, Burton made an appearance as himself on NBC's ''[[Community (TV Series)|Community]]'' in the episodes [[Intermediate Documentary Filmmaking]] and [[Geothermal Escapism]].\n\nBurton has appeared as a fictionalized, humorous version of himself on ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'', first appearing in the episode \"[[The Toast Derivation]]\", in which he almost attends a party thrown by Sheldon (before swearing off Twitter), in November 2012 in the episode \"[[The Habitation Configuration]]\", in which he appears on \"Fun With Flags\" in exchange for lunch and gas money, and again in the November 2014 episode \"[[The Champagne Reflection]]\", in which he returns for the 232nd episode of \"Fun With Flags\" in exchange for Sheldon deleting his contact details.\n\nIn 2012, he had a recurring role as dean Paul Haley on the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] series [[Perception (U.S. TV series)|''Perception'']]. For the second season (2013), he became part of the regular cast.\n\nIn 2014, he had a guest appearance in an introduction section for the 200th episode of Achievement Hunter's show, ''Achievement Hunter Weekly Update'' (AHWU). In May 2014, he appeared as a guest on the [[YouTube]] channel [[SciShow]], explaining the science behind [[Double rainbow|double]], [[Tertiary rainbow|tertiary]], and [[Quaternary rainbow|quaternary]] rainbows. Late in 2014, he had another guest appearance on a 24-hour Extra Life, a fundraising organization for Children's Miracle Network hospitals, stream by [[Rooster Teeth]]. Burton has also taped a [[recycling]] field trip for YouTube.\n\nIn 2017, Burton began a podcast titled \"LeVar Burton Reads\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nerdist.com/levar-burtons-new-podcast-is-like-reading-rainbow-for-adults/ |title=LeVar Burton's New Podcast is Like Reading Rainbow for Adults |last=Ratcliffe |first=Amy |date=June 28, 2017 |publisher=Nerdist}}</ref> Each episode features Burton reading a short story.\n\n===Directing===\nThroughout the 1990s and early 2000s, Burton directed episodes for each of the various ''Star Trek'' series then in production. He has directed more ''Star Trek'' episodes than any other former regular cast member.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000996/ |title=LeVar Burton |website=IMDb |access-date=April 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has also directed episodes of ''[[Charmed]]'', ''[[JAG (TV series)|JAG]]'', ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]'', and ''[[Soul Food (TV series)|Soul Food: The Series]]'', as well as the miniseries ''[[Miracle's Boys]]'' and the biopic ''[[The Tiger Woods Story]]''. He also directed the 1999 [[Disney Channel Original Movie]] ''[[Smart House (film)|Smart House]]'' starring [[Katey Sagal]], [[Kevin Kilner]] and [[Jessica Steen]].\n\nHis first theatrical film direction was ''[[Blizzard (film)|Blizzard]]'' (2003), for which he received a \"Best of Fest\" award from the [[Chicago International Children's Film Festival]], and a [[Genie Award]] nomination for his work on the film's theme song, \"Center of My Heart\".\n\nBurton is on the board of directors for the [[Directors Guild of America]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLeVar Burton married Stephanie Cozart-Burton,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://matineeclassics.com/celebrities/actors/levar_burton/details/ |title=Matinee Classics |date=February 16, 1957 |publisher=Matinee Classics |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216062001/http://matineeclassics.com/celebrities/actors/levar_burton/details/ |archive-date=December 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> a professional make-up artist, in 1992. He and his wife currently live in [[Sherman Oaks]], California.<ref name=\"Bio\" />  LeVar Burton has two children, a daughter Michaela \"Mica\" with his wife, and a son, Eian Burton (born 1980) from a previous relationship.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/02/02/Actor-Levar-Burton-has-paid-8863-in-overdue-child/5831444546000/ |title=Actor Levar Burton has paid $8,863 in overdue child... |date=February 2, 1984 |publisher=United Press International}}</ref> Mica was an employee of [[Rooster Teeth]]'s news division, The Know.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theknow.roosterteeth.com/ |title=The Know |website=theknow.roosterteeth.com}}</ref>\nBurton is also a fan of [[Soccer|English football]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/levarburton/status/854057675327287297 |title=Levar Burton |website=Twitter.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/levarburton/status/854069154982182912 |title=Levar Burton |website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\nAlthough raised Catholic and at one point studying to become a priest,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2018/11/levar-burton-skeleton/566489/ |title=LeVar Burton on Pursuing the Priesthood Before Acting |last=Fadulu |first=Lola |date=2018-11-07 |website=The Atlantic |language=en-US |access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> Burton no longer identifies with any religion, saying: \"I walked away from the seminary, I walked away from Catholicism, I walked away from organized religion because I felt that there was more for me to explore in the world, and that I could do that without adhering to one specific belief system or another.\"<ref>{{Cite podcast |url=http://www.levarburtonpodcast.com |title=Episode 15: \"Unassigned Territory\" by Stephanie Powell Watts |website=Levar Burton Reads |host=Levar Burton |date=January 30, 2018 |time=38:52 |access-date=November 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Burton joined the board of directors for the [[AIDS Research Alliance]], a non-profit, medical research organization dedicated to finding a cure for AIDS.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pr.com/press-release/436088 |title=Emmy Award Winner LeVar Burton Joins AIDS Research Alliance's Board of Directors |date=September 11, 2012 |publisher=AIDS Research Alliance |access-date=June 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Burton was one of the five inaugural honorees to the Sacramento Walk of Stars.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sacramentowalkofstars.com/ |title=Sacramento Walk of Stars |last=<!--Not stated--> |date=2016 |website=sacramentowalkofstars.com |publisher=Sacramento Walk of Stars |access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> In 2019, Sacramento named LeVar Burton Park in his honor. The park is located in the Meadowview neighborhood, down the street from the house where Burton and his sisters grew up.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/585499/sacramento-park-renamed-after-levar-burton-reading-rainbow |title=Sacramento Has Renamed a Local Park After Reading Rainbow Host LeVar Burton |last=Rossen |first=Jake |date=2019-06-12 |website=MentalFloss.Com |publisher=Mental Floss |access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{main|LeVar Burton filmography}}\n\n==Awards and honors==\n===Awards===\n{{Citations needed|section|date=February 2019}}\n====Nominations====\n* 1977 \u2013 [[Emmy]] \u2013 Outstanding Lead Actor for a Single Performance in a Drama or Comedy Series \u2013 ''Roots'' (Part 1, \"Kunta Kinte\")\n* 1998, 2001, 2005 \u2013 [[Image Awards]] variously for Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series and Outstanding Youth or Children's Series/Special \u2014 ''Reading Rainbow'' (both as Self and as Executive Producer)\n* 1991, 1992, 1994, 1995, 1999 \u2013 [[Daytime Emmy]] \u2013 Outstanding Children's Series \u2013 ''Reading Rainbow'' (Executive Producer)\n* 1985, 1986, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2003, 2005, 2006, 2007 \u2013 Daytime Emmy \u2013 Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series \u2014 ''Reading Rainbow'' (Self)\n* 2004 \u2013 [[Genie Award]] \u2013 Best Achievement in Music-Original Song \u2013 ''Blizzard'' (Co-composer \"Center of My Heart\")\n* 2006 \u2013 [[Black Reel Award]] \u2013 Best Director-Television \u2013 ''Miracle's Boys''\n\n====Wins====\n* 1990 \u2013 Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7030 Hollywood Blvd. ''for television achievement''\n* 1992 \u2013 [[Peabody Award]] \u2013 ''Reading Rainbow'' (as executive producer of episode, \"The Wall\")\n* 1994, 1996, 1999, 2002, 2003 \u2013 [[Image Award]] \u2013 ''variously for'' Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series and Outstanding Youth or Children's Series/Special \u2013 ''Reading Rainbow'' (both as Self and as Executive Producer)\n* 2000 \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album]] \u2013 ''The Autobiography of Martin Luther King Jr.''\n* 1990, 1993, 1996, 1997, 1998, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2005, 2007 \u2013 Daytime Emmy \u2013 [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Children's Series|Outstanding Children's Series]] \u2013 ''[[Reading Rainbow]]'' (Executive Producer)\n* 2001, 2002 \u2013 Daytime Emmy \u2013  [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer in Children's Programming|Outstanding Performer in a Children's Series